<FIRST>u i AM-BalloonCrash 3rdLd-Writethru   08-14 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloon Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0757,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>13 Killed In Crash, Described as Worst Such Accident in Ballooning
History</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th pvs, `Ken Watts...' to CORRECT name of news organization;
pickup 7th pvs, `The civil...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALICE SPRINGS, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hot-air balloon collided with
another 2,000 feet over the Australian outback Sunday, plunging to
the ground and killing all 13 people aboard, officials said.
   An aviation expert called it the worst such accident in the
history of ballooning.
   Police said the balloon crashed during a sightseeing trip over a
desert near the central Australian town of Alice Springs.
   Witnesses said the sensed the tragedy before the collision
occurred.
   ``I could see one of the balloons rising fast under another
one,'' said a West German tourist, Irene Fielder, who was in a
third balloon. ``The lower balloon then came up and hit the other
balloon. Its top was touching the basket and it was shaking the
passengers around. I knew something horrible was going to happen.''
   Ken Watts, who was piloting a balloon four miles from where the
accident occurred, told the Australian Associated Press: ``It just
folded up and plummeted to earth. Myself and my passengers were
sickened.''
   The Civil Aviation Authority and the Bureau of Air Safety banned
all balloon flights over Alice Springs while they investigated the
accident.
   Northern Territory police identified the victims as 11
Australians, an Italian and a Dane.
   News reports said three of the victims apparently jumped out at
the last moment to try to save themselves.
   The 10 others were found huddled together in the woven basket
attached to the canopy filled with Liquid Propane Gas, officials
said. The 13 aboard were believed to include a pilot and 12
tourists.
   A spokesman for another company, Outback Ballooning, said the
balloon that crashed was owned by locally-based Toddy's Ballooning,
but no spokesman from the company was unavailable for comment.
   It took police three hours to remove the bodies, which were
wedged tighty in the bottom of the basket. The balloon fabric fell
in a heap beside the basket, which landed between two small trees
in rugged open scrubland about 10 miles from the Alice Springs
airport.
   Tourists go ballooning from Alice Springs to see nearby Ayers
Rock, a sacred aboriginal site and one of the world's biggest
monoliths.
   In Brisbane, former World Balloon champion Roger Meadmore
described the crash as the worst in the history of the sport.
   ``In the 206-year history of ballooning, no balloon that was
airworthy and properly maintained has ever crashed,'' he said.
``This is the worst balloon fatality in history and it is a
terrible thing for ballooning and a terrible thing for Australian
tourism.''
   It was the second fatal ballooning crash in nine days. On Aug.
5, pilot Robert A. Mock as killed when his balloon deflated at
3,000 feet during a national competition in Baton Rouge, La.
   Armond Edwards, an investigator for the National Transportation
Safety Board, said that Mock's balloon was leaking before take-off.
</TEXT>
