<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 0059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike     08-14 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston Strike a Family Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ask anyone in Shirley Harrison's coal-mining
family what the United Mine Workers' strike is about, and the
answer will have nothing to do with money.
   They all believe that Pittston Coal Group has drafted a contract
designed to break the union.
   ``And we're going to fight like hell to see that they don't,''
Mrs. Harrison said.
   At a recent UMW rally at the Russell County courthouse in this
town in far western Virginia, Mrs. Harrison and her two daughters
were singing union songs while her husband, a disabled miner, stood
by. One brother was arrested for participating in a sit-down
demonstration on the front steps and another brother, a strike
captain, was videotaping the entire scene.
   The perception that Pittston is out to bust the union, which the
company disputes, is the main reason behind a bargaining deadlock.
Neither side expected an end to the stalemate as negotiators
prepared for their 139th bargaining session Tuesday. Talks began in
November 1987. The strike is in its fifth month.
   The issue of survival for Pittston's 1,695 union employees
caused wildcat sympathy strikes by about 46,000 UMW members at
other coal companies in 10 states last month. The wildcat strikers
returned to work the week of July 17.
   ``It's something we fight for from the heart because it's in the
heart. Coal mining is our way of life here,'' said Mrs. Harrison,
50, whose father, grandfather and great-grandfather mined the rich
coal veins of southwestern Virginia.
   In a normal summer, Mrs. Harrison said, she would be organizing
family picnics and barbecues at their Castlewood home. Now the
relatives gather at rallies, demonstrations and court hearings.
   ``We're closer than we've ever been,'' she said. ``Pittston is
actually making families and the union stronger.''
   The issues have not fundamentally changed since Pittston broke
away from the group of coal companies that negotiated a national
contract with the UMW last year.
   Union officials have portrayed Pittston's proposals as an
assault on the families whose forefathers were digging coal for the
company and its predecessors even before the UMW began organizing
the coalfields in the 1920s.
   Pittston President Michael Odom said the main issue for the
company, which exports 65 percent of its coal, is operational
flexibility. The company needs to cut labor costs if it hopes to
continue competing in the global market, he said.
   The company wants to operate its mines on a 7-day-a-week,
24-hour-a-day schedule, ease work rules, cut health care and
pension costs and contract out more labor.
   Odom said the company is offering higher wages and an
independent pension plan that is better than the industry-wide plan.
   UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said that since 1984, Pittston has
been transferring coal reserves to new non-union coal mining
subsidiaries while laying off union employees. Corcoran contended
that Pittston is trying to gradually become a non-union operation.
   Odom denies that, pointing to a company promise to try to
maintain employment at the pre-strike level of 1,695.
   The company, however, is offering a contract without a
successorship clause. Such a clause requires that if any of
Pittston's 12 union coal companies is sold, the new owner must
honor the union contract and keep the union workforce.
</TEXT>
