<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett-Budget     08-14 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett-Budget,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Difficult Choices' Needed to Raise Funds for Drug War, Bennett Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug policy director William J. Bennett says
he doesn't think new taxes are needed to wage his expanded war on
drugs, but Congress must ``make some difficult choices'' to find
the money.
   Meanwhile, Bush budget director Richard G. Darman said the
administration may be forced to consider raising taxes next year
unless Congress agrees to cuts in Medicare and other entitlement
programs.
   Bennett on Sunday defended Nancy Reagan's ``Just Say No''
campaign and other Reagan administration efforts to combat drugs,
saying that drug users themselves _ not failed government policies
_ are to blame for the way the problem has spread through society.
   Asked on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' if he would recommend raising
taxes as part of his new anti-drug strategy, Bennett replied,
``Don't think we need taxes.''
   But he insisted, ``The money will be there. We will put our
cards on the table. We will suggest what we want to do and we will
propose spending more money. Then we will see what the Congress
wants to do.
   ``It means making some difficult choices,'' he said.
   Bennett by law must forward a new national strategy for fighting
drugs to Congress by Sept. 5. It is expected to call for a major
boost in federal spending and emphasize both tougher penalties for
individual drug use and mandatory treatment for addicts.
   Bennett was asked if his approach marks a reversal from the
Reagan administration policy, which cut funds for treatment and
emphasized drug interdiction and arrests of kingpins.
   The $21 billion spent fighting drugs during the Reagan
administration ``wasn't wasted, and it wasn't all wrong,'' said
Bennett. ``There were some real successes during the Reagan era.
   ``I don't think anyone can deny that drugs are pervasive
throughout much of America,'' said Bennett, although casual drug
use is down.
   ``Although some people like to criticize the educational efforts
and the first lady's efforts, they obviously have had some
effect,'' said Bennett.
   ``It's the people who are taking drugs that are causing these
tragedies, not the government,'' he said.
   Darman, director of the Office of Management and Budget, said he
will recommend that Bush seek fiscal 1991 cuts in the growth of
Medicare, agriculture, veterans and other entitlement programs, but
not Social Security.
   Darman, on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' repeated Bush's resolve not
to raise taxes, but said:
   ``When the Congress comes back in September, if they don't fully
implement the bipartisan budget agreement, we will have to have a
sequester, and it will drive us toward having to face the tax issue
the following year, which we shouldn't do.''
   He said the administration and the legislative branch must find
savings of $25 billion to $30 billion to avoid an automatic,
across-the-board cut under the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings deficit
reduction law.
   He said Medicare payments for doctors' fees have risen ``at
about 15 percent a year. That can't go on forever; it's going to
consume the whole budget. So we have to restrain the growth there.''
   ``There are going to be some wealthy doctors, presumably, who
aren't quite so wealthy in the future,'' he predicted.
</TEXT>
