<FIRST>r w PM-Leland-US     08-14 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland-US,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Leland's Plane `Basically Disintegrated'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Leland-Reax, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are ready to help investigate
the crash in Ethiopia of a plane carrying Rep. Mickey Leland and
his party if that country's government requests aid, a Pentagon
official says.
   Navy Capt. Stan Bloyer said on Sunday the retrieval of remains
was expected to begin today at the mountainside crash site.
   ``We would like to extend our deepest sympathy and condolence to
the families involved,'' he said.
   The bodies were to be flown by helicopter to the village of
Dembidola north of the crash site, then ferried to the Ethiopian
capital of Addis Ababa by C-130 cargo plane.
   They were expected to arrive in the United States within two to
three days on board a C-141 medical evacuation aircraft, after a
stop at Torrejon Air Base near Madrid, Spain, where full mortuary
facilities are available, Bloyer said.
   Forensic and medical specialists were dispatched from Addis
Ababa to aid in the retrieval work.
   Bloyer said U.S. officials are ready to assist should the
Ethiopian government request help in conducting an inquiry into the
crash.
   Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., who was aboard the MH-60 search and
rescue helicopter that first spotted the wreckage, relayed ``that
in his judgment there was no possibility of survivors,'' Bloyer
said.
   The State Department also expressed condolences, saying the
crash ``apparently has resulted in the death of all those aboard.''
   ``The condition of the plane is extensively destroyed, basically
disintegrated,'' Bloyer said. ``The wreckage is located on a ravine
on a very steep mountainside and there is evidence of a post-impact
fire.''
   Bloyer said it was unknown whether the pilot was headed for an
alternate destination when the plane crashed, but it did not appear
to be attempting an emergency landing.
   ``It appeared ... that it just impacted at cruise speed in the
side of the mountain,'' he said.
   Bloyer said the area where the crash occurred had been searched
earlier, but bad weather had made it difficult to find the
wreckage. The improved visibility on Sunday was a major factor in
locating the crash site in the rugged mountain terrain, he said.
   Sixteen people were believed on board, but Bloyer said officials
were unsure how many Ethiopian observers had joined the delegation,
making an immediate exact count impossible.
   Leland, a Texas Democrat who heads the House Select Committee on
Hunger, was bound for the Fugnido refugee camp near the Sudanese
border when the Twin Otter plane vanished in bad weather on Aug. 7.
He was accompanied by eight Americans, including three members of
his staff, a friend of the congressman, three workers for the U.S.
Agency for International Development, and the wife of one of the
AID officials.
   The U.S. government had mobilized a massive search team for the
rescue effort, involving hundreds of people and a variety of
aircraft, including U-2 spy planes.
</TEXT>
