<FIRST>r w PM-Speaker'sOffice     08-14 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speaker's Office,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley's New Digs: Life at the Top is Closer to the Floor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Tom Foley knows his way around
the power corridors of the nation's capital. It's finding his new
office that occasionally has him doing an about-face.
   ``Old habits die hard,'' said Foley, admitting that he
occasionally leaves the House floor and finds himself heading down
the stairs toward his old office.
   For eight years, first as Democratic whip and then as majority
leader, the cozy suite on the ground floor in the original part of
the Capitol building was home to Foley, his staff and his aging dog
Alice.
   Tourists wandering the main hallway would often peek inside
trying to catch a glimpse of someone famous. When mice were
discovered scampering about, Foley brought in a cat.
   Numbered paint chips of varying shades of yellow were taped to a
wall for months.
   Now, along with the challenges of being one of the pre-eminent
politicians in the country, Foley has a new office suite just off
the House floor.
   ``All in all it would have been convenient and comfortable not
to move,'' said Foley. ``It doesn't feel like home. It is still
unfamiliar, slightly awkward.''
   Foley knows well that along with the power of his new office
come the trappings. Besides, his new office is convenient to the
floor and the cloakrooms where much of the day-to-day business of
the House is conducted.
   A month after moving, Foley and his staff are settling in
although boxes of files are still stacked in the corners and
painters still wander around touching up.
   Foley's private office looks a lot like his old one.
   The Texas longhorn orange walls that former Speaker Jim Wright
left behind are now the same vivid blue of Foley's previous office.
The comfortable grouping of living room furniture is the same as
are most of the paintings.
   ``I don't care for the institutional beige or green common to
most government buildings,'' said Foley. ``I prefer either white or
pale or very bright colors.''
   Even though his ceremonial office, where he meets the press
daily and greets some visitors, has a battleship-sized desk,
Foley's private office does not.
   ``I don't feel comfortable sitting behind a desk when talking
with people,'' said Foley, who spends most of his time in a
comfortable easy chair on the phone or wandering in and out of his
staff's offices.
   While his former office suite was like a crowded rabbit's warren
the new one is spacious. Staffers complain it is not as conducive
to the intense give-and-take sessions common in their former
quarters.
   The offices look out over the east front of the Capitol, with a
view of the Library of Congress and the Supreme Court through the
trees of a grass plaza.
   The new suite dates back only to the early 1960s when the east
front of the Capitol was extended, though Foley's ceremonial office
dates to the Civil War era and the nearby women members' lounge was
the room where John Quincy Adams died.
   Foley said he plans ``no major renovations,'' but the dining
room will receive a facelift as the new speaker wants to have a
more formal setting for lunches with such people as visiting
foreign dignitaries.
   As for Alice, Foley said his pet has ``made the adjustment
pretty well. We haven't really done that much except move furniture
around. It will take a couple of months to feel comfortable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
