<FIRST>r w PM-Pell-Schneider     08-14 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pell-Schneider,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pell Fundraising Inactive as Schneider Gears up for Senate Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee and a veteran of 28 years in Congress,
isn't acting like a politician interested in six more years when
his current term expires.
   While other senators up for re-election next year have already
raised hundreds of thousands of dollars _ and in some cases several
million _ Pell's fundraising activities have been moribund.
   The Rhode Island Democrat received only a single $5,000
contribution in the first half of this year despite the threat of a
strong Republican opponent for the first time in nearly two decades.
   Pell aides insist he plans to run for the seat but that he has
his own timetable and will begin fundraising when he is ready.
   Republicans, however, say Claudine Schneider, an aggressive and
popular five-term GOP congresswoman, has a good chance of winning
the seat even if Pell does run. They say the incumbent could be
vulnerable because of his age, the historic difficulties that
Foreign Relations Committee chairmen have faced and his passionate
interest in psychic phenomena.
   Democrats hold a 55-45 advantage in the Senate, and Pell is one
of six Democratic incumbents being targeted by national GOP
strategists for 1990.
   Pell's lack of fundraising contrasts sharply to the other 30
senators who have established campaign committees for a 1990
re-election bid. They have raised an average of nearly $750,000
each during the first six months of this year, according to
campaign disclosure reports filed at the Federal Election
Commission.
   The numbers are more curious considering the 70-year-old
Democrat is likely to face his toughest race since his hard-fought
1972 victory over Republican John H. Chafee, who won the state's
other Senate seat four years later.
   Next year Pell likely would face Miss Schneider, who has all but
announced a Senate run.
   Miss Schneider reported more than $200,000 in campaign
contributions to her House re-election committee for the
January-June FEC reporting period.
   ``When he knows he could face someone as aggressive as Claudine
Schneider, I don't see how he can afford to take that passive
attitude,'' said Wendy DeMocker, a spokeswoman for the National
Republican Senatorial Committee.
   Pell aides say the senator's lack of fundraising is merely an
outgrowth of his concern that the campaign season has become too
long.
   ``He has said repeatedly he has every intention of running,''
said a senior Pell aide who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``He just feels very strongly that the campaign process has gotten
out of hand.''
   Pell does have $444,686 in his campaign coffers in preparation
for 1990, but 21 of the 30 other senators running next year have
more, according to FEC documents.
   Pell is one of the most popular politicians in Rhode Island
history, winning his Senate seat in 1960 by defeating two former
governors in a primary. He has been a leading advocate for the arts
and education and in 1986 became chairman of the powerful Foreign
Relations Committee.
   But chairmen of that committee have in the past have suffered at
re-election time, attacked by challengers who charge they are
paying too much attention to international problems and not enough
to parochial concerns. Five years ago, Democrat Paul Simon unseated
then-Foreign Relations Chairman Charles Percy, R-Ill.
   Miss Schneider has statewide recognition since Rhode Island has
only two House seats. And she is the type of Republican that
Democratic-dominated Rhode Island likes _ a liberal on social
issues with a strong environmental record.
   Age also could become a factor. Miss Schneider is 42, the same
age Pell was when he first came to the Senate nearly 30 years ago.
   Pell will be 71 in November and would be 78 at the end of
another six-year term.
   Pell, however, would still be a youngster compared to his
predecessor. Theodore Green came to the Senate at age 69 and
retired in 1960 at age 93.
</TEXT>
