<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 0204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PetRemains Bjt   08-14 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pet Remains, Bjt,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pet Remains Recycled Into Animal Feed, Fertilizer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a question many pet owners would rather not
ask: What happens to the remains of the hundreds of thousands of
dogs and cats that are destroyed each year?
   Part of the answer is clear, though gruesome: As many as a third
wind up in rendering plants, where their remains are broken down
into a variety of products.
   Which products, however, is harder to say.
   Over the years various reports have traced pet remains to soap
and cosmetics, which are made with animal fats.
   Last week The Wall Street Journal, in an article on New York
City's Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, said
unclaimed stray pets destroyed at the society's shelter are
collected by a rendering plant in New Jersey where they are
``boiled down to byproducts used in cosmetics and other products.''
The article said a kitten could wind up ``as a bar of soap.''
   Are New Yorkers washing themselves with their former pets?
   Vito Turso, spokesman for the Sanitation Department, said
although the city pays $150,000 a year to Darling-Delaware Inc. to
collect the carcasses, he did not know what the renderer does with
them.
   The Newark, N.J., plant manager, Anton Weir, referred calls to
John Grayson, division manager. A half-dozen calls over three days
to Grayson were not returned.
   What really happens to pet remains brought to rendering plants?
Probably nothing sinister, according to an industry spokesman.
   Dr. Russell John, director of technical services for the
National Renderers Association, said almost all the small animals
collected by renderers are turned into animal feed or fertilizer.
   Soaps and cosmetics require high quality, white animal fats, he
explained. Those come mostly from cattle, not dogs and cats, and
accordingly they are acquired from slaughterhouses, not animal
shelters.
   Gerald McEwen, vice president for science with the Cosmetic,
Toiletry and Fragrance Association, said it ``boggles the mind'' to
think cat or dog remains would be used in cosmetics, given
manufacturers' needs for pure beef tallow.
   Even if pet remains are not in personal cosmetics, the problem
of disposing of animal carcasses is a disturbing and persistent one
for the nation's animal shelters and veterinary facilities, which
have three options: cremate the animals, bury them in a sanitary
landfill or turn them over to a renderer.
   Cremation is either illegal or impractical in many large cities,
including New York, Los Angeles and Washington, and landfills are
closing around the country.
   That leaves renderers, who cook down animal remains to obtain
substances used in a variety of manufactured products. In Los
Angeles, for example, remains are used to make fertilizer.
   Such uses ``do offend some people's sensibilities,'' said
Barbara Cassidy of the Humane Society of the United States.
   But given the vast numbers of stray or unwanted pets that must
be destroyed each year _ the Los Angeles County shelter alone puts
about 25,000 dogs and cats to sleep _ rendering is widely viewed as
a form of recycling.
   ``You're grateful if anyone will come and take the bodies
away,'' said Ingrid Newkirk, director of People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals and a former director of a Washington, D.C.,
animal shelter.
   ``They don't keep well. You have to put them in giant freezers.
It's hideous. A lousy, lousy situation,'' she said.
   Shelters that turn animal remains over to renderers usually
offer pet owners an alternative, including cremation and burial in
a pet cemetery. Cremation costs between $35 and $50, but a casket
and cemetery plot can cost more than $500.
   A person who puts an animal up for adoption in a shelter is told
the beast will be put to sleep if a suitable owner cannot be found
within a few days.
   But, ``usually, people don't want to deal with the remains,''
said Ed Cubrda, director of the Los Angeles SPCA. ``A lot of people
don't know what happens to them, and a lot don't want to know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
