<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-14 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar moved up against the Japanese yen
during afternoon trading on Monday, while share prices on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange recovered morning losses.
   The dollar opened at 141.85 yen, up 1.75 yen from last Friday's
140.10-yen close, and finished at 141.93 yen. It varied between
141.48 yen and 141.95 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 6.84 points in
trading Friday, declined another 41.34 points, or 0.12 percent, to
close at 34,671.62 points.
   The U.S. currency's jump at the opening of the Tokyo market
followed gains in New York last Friday as investors were reassured
by economic indicators released in Washington, said a trader with
the Bank of Tokyo.
   The U.S. producer price index for July fell by 0.4 percent,
while the retail price index for July rose by 0.9 percent from the
previous month, indicating stability in the U.S. economy, analysts
said.
   ``The market started higher, but sales in the interbank market
and profit-taking pushed the dollar downward,'' said a trader at
Mitsui Bank.
   But the market appeared locked into a fixed range, she said.
   ``There were buyers when the dollar hit a low, and sellers when
it reached a high,'' she said.
   On the stock exchange, trading was thin with many market traders
taking summer holidays this week, said Kazuhiro Nomura, a trader at
New Japan Securities.
   ``Being a Monday morning, many traders were taking a
wait-and-see attitude,'' he said.
   There was some selective trading of high-tech issues, however,
he said.
   Nomura predicted there would be little movement this week.
</TEXT>
