<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     08-14 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Abyss' Makes $8.6 Million Weekend Box Office Splash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Abyss'' dove into the summer's pool of
blockbuster movies with an estimated $8.6 million box office splash
in its first weekend, putting the film second only to
``Parenthood,'' an industry source said.
   ``Parenthood,'' directed by Ron Howard, took in an estimated
$9.6 million, said the source, who asked not to be identified. In
third-place was ``A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child,''
bringing in about $8.3 million.
   ``The Abyss,'' the $43 million underwater science-fiction drama
by 20th Century Fox, made a solid opening Wednesday, taking in $2.1
million at the national box office for a per-screen average of
$1,406, Daily Variety reported.
   The movie stars Ed Harris as the foreman of an experimental
underwater oil rig commandeered by a group of Navy SEALS to salvage
a wrecked U.S. nuclear submarine. Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio plays
the foreman's wife and designer of the oil rig who makes contact
with alien beings.
   Much of the film was shot in the cooling tank of an unfinished
nuclear power plant in South Carolina that was filled with 7.5
million gallons of water.
   Cast and crew spent about 40 percent of a 3{-month shooting
schedule underwater. The work required director James Cameron,
actors, camera operators and a squad of technicians to remain
beneath the surface for up to 10 hours a day, often until 4 a.m.
   ``Parenthood'' stars Steve Martin, Tom Hulce, Jason Robards and
Dianne Wiest in an ensemble family drama that also features Mary
Steenburgen, Rick Moranis, Keanu Reeves and Martha Plimpton.
</TEXT>
