<FIRST>r a PM-Milwaukee-DrugCrime     08-14 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milwaukee-Drug Crime,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summer of Violence Has Milwaukee Officials Scrambling for Solutions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LA-Gang Backlash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL L. BRAUN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city that thought itself free of the worst of
big-city problems has witnessed a summer of drive-by shootings,
murders and drug running, with violent crime nearly double what it
was a year ago.
   Queen Hyler, whose son was beaten unconscious by a street gang,
says Milwaukee residents are fed up.
   ``It's going to be turned around in Milwaukee. People are not
going to put up with this,'' said Ms. Hyler. ``And I'm prepared to
die for it. I refuse to give one inch to the drug dealers.''
   The sudden outbreak of violence and illegal drugs has shocked
residents of this city, which has strong ethnic roots, a tradition
of progressive government and a history of low crime rates.
   Through the first seven months of 1989, there were 69 murders,
compared to 54 for the same period last year. There were 1,020
violent crimes through July 1, compared to 565 for the first six
months of 1988.
   Acting Police Chief LeRoy A. Jahnke said the majority of the
city's violence has been drug-related.
   Jahnke has increased overtime staffing, putting 48 more officers
on the streets between 10 p.m. and 2 a.m., when many shootings have
occurred. A new system that will allow clerks to write reports
formerly written by police officers should put 100 more officers on
the streets.
   To curb the growing supply of arms on city streets, Alderwoman
Larraine McNamara-McGraw said she would support an ordinance
banning the sale of small-caliber weapons.
   She also praised a program introduced in late July by Mayor John
O. Norquist, encouraging residents to turn in unwanted firearms to
police stations.
   After her teen-age son Byron was severely beaten by gang members
last year, Ms. Hyler took to social activism and became president
of the People United Association.
   Her group has staged marches and vigils this summer to call
attention to the growing crime problems in Milwaukee, particularly
on the highly segregated North Side where most of the city's black
population lives.
   Ms. Hyler said she worked hard to make a home in Milwaukee, and
she will not let drugs ruin her neighborhood.
   ``Somebody has to move, and I'm not going,'' she said.
   Still, she said, fighting the image of the drug dealer is often
difficult because it frequently takes a few years for authorities
to convict a violator. By that time, she said, young people have
already been dazzled by the dealer's Mercedes, gold chains and
other luxuries.
   ``It's hard to tell a kid that's not the right road,'' she said,
noting that working for the minimum wage of $3.65 an hour is not an
attractive alternative to the lucrative drug business.
   In addition to its lobbying efforts, People United offers young
people scholarships, group discussion sessions and constructive
youth recreation.
   ``We try to make kids feel good about themselves,'' and give
them good role models, she said.
   Ms. McNamara-McGraw agreed with that approach.
   She said education can raise young people's sense of dignity,
and can dissuade youths from ``buying into'' the drug world.
   ``We're a salvageable city,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890814-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 0544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TelephoneWorkers-Insurance     08-14 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Telephone Workers-Insurance,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Insurance Costs To Be Major Labor Issue In Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Phone Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle over health insurance cost-sharing that
helped spark phone workers' strikes in 20 states is likely to crop
up in many industries in the 1990s, according to business and labor
officials.
   Fifty percent of the union leaders and 38 percent of the
business leaders surveyed in a recent study commissioned by
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. said employee payments for health
insurance would be one of the top six negotiating priorities for
this year.
   ``Health care has been a major issue on the bargaining table and
as we progress into the '90s, it will become the No. 1 or No. 2
issue,'' Lorrie McHugh, a spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO in
Washington, said Friday.
   ``It certainly does seem to be a trend that will be a major
focal point with the rate health care costs are growing,'' said
Karen Brigham of the Chamber of Commerce of the United States.
   Health insurance has been the principal bargaining issue in the
contract talks among the seven ``Baby Bells'' and the unions that
represent their more than 300,000 workers.
   Workers at NYNEX Corp., Bell Atlantic Corp. and Pacific Telesis
went on strike last week, and workers struck Ameritech on Sunday.
   Workers and company officials reached agreement at BellSouth,
Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. and U S West. In the latter two,
strikes were averted when the companies agreed to surrender their
demands that workers pay a share of health insurance premiums,
which up to now had been 100 percent company paid.
   Earlier this year, AT&amp;T averted a threatened strike by
abandoning demands that workers pay a share of health premiums.
   Ms. Brigham said health care costs have been rising at more than
twice the rate of inflation in the past few years.
   ``Employers realize they cannot absorb these increases year
after year and remain competitive,'' she said. ``Part of the
solution is to inject a little more individual responsibility into
the picture.''
   Ms. McHugh agreed on the need to get health care costs under
control but disagreed on the solution.
   ``We recognize the fact that as health care costs continue to
escalate, there needs to be an equitable solution, but if you
continue to shift the burden, you create barriers to care for many
working Americans,'' she said.
   The AFL-CIO's preferred solution, she said, is a national health
insurance plan. She said the umbrella labor organization will start
a campaign in November for an overhaul of the nation's health care
system.
   Myles Calvey, business manager of the Quincy, Mass.-based Local
2222 of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, said
NYNEX was profitable enough to be able to pay its workers' health
insurance coverage.
   But Peter Cronin, a spokesman for New England Telephone, a
division of NYNEX, said the company would be unusual if it
continued providing full health insurance coverage at no cost to
the workers.
   ``The way things have developed because of the high costs of
medical care, about 80 percent of the businesses in the country
require some kind of co-payment. The unusual thing is we have been
able to continue full payment as long as we have,'' Cronin said.
</TEXT>
