<FIRST>r a PM-EngineFailure-727 1stLd-Writethru a0462 08-14 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Engine Failure-727, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engine on 727 Apparently Disintegrates During Takeoff Attempt at
Denver</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10 pvs, `The No. 2...' to CORRECT location of No.
2 engine to fuselage, sted stabilizer as sent, CLARIFY that plane is designed
to take off with all three engines, INSERT name of maker of DC-10; picks
up 11th graf, `On July 19...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airline official said there was no connection
between the tail engine failure that forced a Continental Airlines
727 to abort a takeoff and recent tail engine problems in DC-10
jetliners.
   An official at Boeing Co., the aircraft's maker, said Sunday's
incident was ``very unusual,'' and added that the company would
want to investigate it.
   Fan blades and other metal pieces of the Pratt &amp; Whitney engine
on the Boeing 727-200 were scattered over a runway at Stapleton
International Airport after the plane's No. 2 engine disintegrated.
   No one was injured.
   The runway was closed for about 90 minutes and the 128
passengers on the plane bound for Portland were put on another
flight. There also were seven crew members aboard when the engine
failed.
   Ron Holthouser, a retired American Airlines pilot from Oakridge,
Ore., said he heard a loud mechanical scream and a pop from the
rear engine during the acceleration for liftoff.
   ``Luckily, it happened on the ground but it was nip and tuck
there,'' Holthouser said.
   ``He did the right thing,'' he said, referring to the pilot's
decision to abort takeoff. ``I give him all the credit in the
world. It was a snap judgment and they didn't have much runway
left.''
   The No. 2 engine is mounted in the fuselage. The 727 also has
two other engines mounted near the rear of the aircraft, and it can
take off with just two engines, although it is designed to take off
with all three, Continental spokesman Ned Walker said.
   The No. 2 engine has come under scrutiny recently in DC-10
aircraft, made by McDonnell Douglas, which are larger than 727s,
but Walker said there is ``no comparison whatsoever to the DC-10
question.''
   On July 19, a United Air Lines DC-10 bound for Chicago from
Denver crashed in an Iowa cornfield while attempting an emergency
landing at the Sioux City airport. Its tail engine exploded in
midflight, apparently severing hydraulic lines that control the
wing and tail flaps. The crash killed 111 people but 185 survived.
   Last week, a Northwest Airlines DC-10 made an emergency landing
in Denver on its way to Minneapolis from Los Angeles after its No.
2 tail engine apparently started disintegrating in flight, nicking
the hydraulic lines but not severing them.
   On Friday, a third DC-10 bound for Denver aborted takeoff in
Boston because of a stalled compressor in the tail-mounted engine,
officials said.
   Walker said engine pieces did not perforate the engine's outer
cover in Sunday's incident.
   Because there were no injuries reported and the engine failure
was contained inside the covering, Walker said an investigation by
federal authorities was not required.
   But Tom Cole, a Boeing spokesman in Seattle, said a contained
engine failure in a 727 was rare and investigators from the
company, the NTSB, Pratt &amp; Whitney and Continental would want to
examine the engine.
   ``It is very unusual to have an engine do that on a 727,'' Cole
said. ``I can't remember the last time it happened, if it actually
ever happened at all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
