<HEAD>Ex-Foreign Minister Leading in Christian Democratic Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Christian Democratic Party
voted in Guatemala's first presidential primary and an unofficial
count indicated party chief Alfonso Cabrera was winning.
   Official results from Sunday's balloting were expected later
today.
   The election date has not been announced, but it is expected to
be late this year. President Vinicio Cerezo's five-year term
expires Jan. 14, 1991.
   Results gathered by the local Emisoras Unidas radio chain
indicated Cabrera, a congressman and former foreign minister under
Cerezo, was leading Rene de Leon Schlotter, a longtime party leader
and former Development Minister, and Cerezo's wife, Raquel Blandon
de Cerezo, who is a lawyer.
   Mrs. Cerezo, director of social welfare for the presidency, has
been active in the party but did not openly campaign for the
nomination.
   The president, a Christian Democrat, has backed Cabrera and
voted in Sunday's election.
   Turnout was estimated at about 120,000.
   Jorge Carpio Nicolle, founder of the National Union of the
Center, and Jorge Serrano Elias of the Joint Action Movement are
virtually assured their party's nominations. Carpio Nicolle
finished second against Cerezo in 1985 and Serrano third.
   Executive committees of the conservative National Renovation and
Revolutionary parties say they back Fernando Andrade, foreign
minister in the 1983-1986 military government of Gen. Oscar
Humberto Mejia Victores and former ambassador of Cerezo's
government to the United Nations. Party conventions must be held to
confirm the nomination.
