<FIRST>r a PM-ShipSunk     08-14 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Sunk,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fish-Processing Ship Sinks Off Alaska; Crew Safe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KETCHIKAN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 166-foot fish-processing ship
carrying up to 18,000 gallons of fuel sank off the coast, but all
68 people aboard were rescued, the Coast Guard said today.
   The ship began to list Saturday evening and by about 9 p.m., the
crew was evacuated to a fishing vessel that had been nearby, said
Coast Guard Petty Officer Greg Robinson. Four crew members were
treated at a hospital for minor injuries.
   The steel-hulled vessel went down in the Tongass Narrows, a
waterway off Ketchikan on Alaska's southern coast, with between
15,000 and 18,000 gallons of fuel, Robinson said. It was not
immediately known how much fuel had escaped.
   Oil slicks were sighted on both sides of Pennock Island, which
is directly across from Ketchikan, Robinson said. Divers reached
the ship Sunday in 144 feet of water, sealing fuel vents to prevent
further seepage of oil, he said.
   Fuel remaining on board will have to be removed, and authorities
were considering raising the boat, which was upright on the sea
floor, Robinson said.
   The cause of the sinking was not immediately known.
   The Coast Guard assumed control of the spill and hired a cleanup
contractor after the vessel's owner refused to contract with a
salvage services to contain any oil slick and to accept financial
responsibility, Robinson said.
   Coast Guard records showed Ocean Pacific Fisheries of Seattle
owned the vessel, but Yak Inc. of Seattle told the Coast Guard it
was the owner, Robinson said. It will be billed for the Coast
Guard's services, he added.
   There was no immediate estimate of cleanup costs. No one
answered the telephone at Yak Inc. on Sunday.
</TEXT>
