<FIRST>r i PM-ChannelSwimmer     08-14 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel Swimmer,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Frustrates American Paraplegic Who Wants to Swim Channel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOLKESTONE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American said today he'll go home
later this week unless the weather improves and allows him to make
an attempt to become the first paraplegic to swim the English
Channel.
   Robert Patterson, of Maryland, N.Y., has been waiting at a
Folkestone hotel for one week to attempt the 20-mile crossing from
England to Cap Gris Nez, France.
   ``I just can't believe that this is happening,'' he said today
of the weather. ``I trained for this for two years. I put my heart
and soul into it.''
   Winds in the channel today were 20 mph and waves were three to
five feet high. The conditions were ``much too rough'' for
swimmers, said Ray Scott, chairman of the Channel Swimming
Association that authenticates the swims.
   ``It's a conspiracy of the fates,'' Scott said. ``But it's no
use swimming in high winds. You get buffeted about in high waves.''
   Weather forecasts were boding early improvement, Scott said.
   Patterson said if he can't swim Tuesday or Wednesday, he will
return home.
   ``I can't get any more demoralized than I am now,'' he said.
``It was excellent weather most of the summer, so this is kind of a
shock.''
   Patterson, 33, became a paraplegic three years ago when he fell
25 feet from a scaffold on a construction site. The accident broke
his spine and paralyzed him from the waist down.
   He swam eight miles across Otsego Lake in upstate New York last
year in six hours, 48 minutes. This June, he swam the lake again,
going nine miles while shaving one hour, two minutes off his time.
   Patterson's training includes weightlifting in the fall and
winter and swimming in the St. Lawrence River on weekends in the
summer. He also takes daily swims in an indoor pool or a local lake.
   Two other paraplegics have attempted to swim the English Channel
but failed.
   Patterson said if thwarted by the weather this time, he doubts
he'll come back for another attempt.
   A 27-year-old woman trying to become the first handicapped woman
to swim the channel is also waiting for the weather to improve,
Scott said.
   Lucyna Krajewska, who has had both legs amputated, attempted the
crossing in 1987 but gave up after covering only six miles in seven
hours.
   Ms. Krajewska, who was born in Poland, defected to West Germany
six years ago. She won the gold medal in the 100-meter freestyle
swim at the Paraolympics in Seoul last year.
</TEXT>
