<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru a0466 08-14 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with strike in Azerbaijan. Pick
up 11th pvs, `Some activists...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Russian workers in Estonia kept up their 6-day-old
strike today, and workers at six factories in the southwestern
republic of Azerbaijan reportedly walked out to support demands of
a new nationalist group.
   In a third Soviet area threatened by nationalist strikes, the
Caucasus mountain republic of Georgia, activists said they will
decide at a mass meeting tonight whether to call a walkout for
Tuesday.
   In Estonia's Baltic Sea capital of Tallinn, strike leaders said
today at least 20,000 Russian workers stayed off the job to protest
a new law that tightens residency requirements for voters and
candidates.
   ``The strike is continuing,'' said strike committee member
Alexei Kutenyov in a telephone interview. He said the committee
expected decisive action on the stoppage from a Kremlin commission
on inter-ethnic affairs by Tuesday, but he did not elaborate.
   State-run Moscow Radio said today the Estonian strike has caused
losses of millions of dollars.
   It said the Estonian law will take the right to vote away from
more than 100,000 non-Estonians in the republic of 1.6 million.
   The new law limits voting to residents who have lived in the
same district for two years or anywhere in Estonia for five years.
Candidates must live in the same place for five years or in Estonia
for 10 years.
   In Azerbaijan, a local journalist reported workers walked out in
the late afternoon at six factories, including a steel plant, in
the capital of Baku.
   Of Baku's estimated 1 million workers, only about 1 percent
joined the stoppage, said Saveli Peretz, deputy chief of
Azerinform, the official Azerbaijani news agency.
   Speaking by telephone, he said the strike call, which was put
forth by the newly formed People's Front of Azerbaijan, would
probably be discussed at a mass meeting in Baku late today.
   The strike was meant to support demands that local leaders
``find political solutions instead of military ones'' to the
republic's ethnic violence, which has caused dozens of deaths, said
activist Aidin Amirbekov in a telephone interview Sunday.
   Some activists in Azerbaijan are also demanding removal of
Soviet troops from the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh and
an end to curfews in the republic, but Amirbekov said authorities
consider relations too tense to take such a step.
   Troops reportedly have been halting clashes in Nagorno-Karabakh
on almost a daily basis.
   Traditionally Shiite Moslem Azerbaijan has been embroiled in a
dispute with neighboring Armenia, whose population is mainly
Christian, over control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region.
Nagorno-Karabakh is part of Azerbaijan but its population is
predominantly Armenian, and Armenia wants to annex it.
   In Estonia, Kutenyov said work had at least partially halted at
46 of the republic's enterprises, mainly in Tallinn and in the
mining town of Kohtla-Jarve. The labor newspaper Trud said Sunday
39 factories were involved in the strike.
   Estonian journalists said today some of the bus lines in Tallinn
were not running. ``That's the most acute thing for us,'' said
Estonian Radio commentator Harry Tiido in a telephone interview.
   Cargo railcars were piling up at Tallinn stations because train
workers were on strike, and the state airline Aeroflot was carrying
only emergency supplies and passengers there, Trud said.
   The strikers, most of whom work in industrial plants, also
object to a new national decision to give Estonia free rein over
its economy. The workers are demanding factories with a
predominantly Russian-speaking labor force remain under supervision
of the national government rather than be handed over to Estonia.
</TEXT>
