<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru   08-14 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0424,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede BONN</HEAD>
<HEAD>West Germany Closes Embassy Packed with East German Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UDPATE with Budapest embassy closed, West German
official meeting with Hungarian official, other details. Changes byline.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government closed its
embassy in Budapest today to stop a flood of East Germans hoping to
go West. About 100 would-be emigrants were locked outside, but 181
occupying the embassy were allowed to remain inside.
   The Foreign Ministry announced Sunday the embassy would be
closed because its ability to assist the stream of East German
refugees was ``totally exhausted.''
   In Bonn, Foreign Ministry spokesman Hanns Schumacher told
reporters those inside the embassy were being cared for by the
diplomatic staff and that Red Cross volunteers were erecting
temporary facilities outside the mission for new arrivals.
   Hungary's foreign minister, Gyula Horn, met today with Juergen
Suedhoff of the Bonn Foreign Ministry for talks focusing on the
situation, said Hungary's official MTI news agency.
   Talks dealt with ``the possible humanitarian solutions'' to the
problem, MTI reported without elaboration.
   Many of those at the embassy in Budapest are East Germans who
were caught trying to reach the West illegally. They are seeking
West German assistance out of fear they will be punished if they
return home.
   Schumacher said 141 adults and 40 children were inside the
compound. He said news reports estimating the number at up to 300
were exaggerated.
   More East Germans are thought to be sheltered in buildings
rented by West Germans.
   West German embassies in other East bloc capitals also have been
deluged by East Germans hoping to emigrate and fearing punishment
if they return home, despite East German assurances they will not
be punished.
   Bonn closed its East Berlin mission on Tuesday, after 131 East
Germans sought refuge there, and West German officials have said it
will not be opened again until normal operations can resume.
   About 20 East Germans were believed to have sought refuge at the
West German diplomatic mission in Prague, Czechoslovakia, but there
were no indications the Bonn government had any plans to close that
facility.
   The crush in Hungary began after that Soviet bloc nation began
dismantling barriers along its Western frontier with neutral
Austria.
   It is estimated at least 1,500 East Germans managed to make
their way to West Germay by going first to Hungary and then
crossing through Austria.
   Many were caught by Hungarian border guards as they tried to get
to Austria, and some took refuge in the West German compound.
   West Germany as a standard practice grants asylum to East
Germans, but West German Foreign Ministry officials have said that
only East Germany can grant the refugees exit visas. Applications
to emigrate often take years to process.
   Dozens of mostly young East Germans spent the night in front of
the Budapest compound despite the announcement the embassy would be
closed. Their numbers had swollen to about 100 by midday, when the
doors closed.
   West Germany expects about 100,000 East Germans to make their
way to West Germany by the end of the year through legal emigration
and escapes.
   Hungarian-language radio today reported that 471 East Germans
were caught trying to escape to Austria over the weekend from
Hungary.
   A Hamburg-based newspaper, The World on Sunday, said the West
German intelligence service has determined that 1.5 million East
Germans out of the population of 16 million want to emigrate to the
West.
   Hungary and Poland have followed the Soviet Union in
implementing political and economic reforms with greater individual
freedoms.
   But East German leader Erich Honecker has not wavered from his
hard-line policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
