<FIRST>r a PM-HospitalStrike     08-14 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Strike,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Workers Begin Three-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 47,000 nurses' aides, pharmacists and
other workers began a three-day strike today at 53 private
hospitals and nursing homes in the New York City area to press for
a raise.
   The strike by Local 1199 of the Drug, Hospital and Health Care
Employees Union began at 7 a.m., according to spokesman Bill Batson.
   The union's members have been working without a contract since
June 30 at the hospitals and nursing homes belonging to the League
of Voluntary Hospitals.
   ``Things are going fine,'' said Steven Alschuler, a spokesman
for the league. ``It's not going to impact patient care in any
serious way.''
   Management employees filled in for strikers. Batson said some
clinics were closed for the duration of the walkout, and some
elective surgery has been postponed.
   The striking union members include nurses' aides, pharmacists,
social and clerical workers, cooks, housekeepers and lab and X-ray
technicians.
   The union is seeking raises of 8.5 percent in each of the next
two years; the hospitals have offered 13 percent over three years.
   No talks were scheduled.
