<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Dependents Begin Returning to Beijing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spouses and children of U.S. Embassy personnel returned to Beijing
on Monday, and they were greeted with flowers,
American flags and hugs.
   The 40 American dependents had been evacuated from China shortly after
the army shot its way into Beijing to crush the
pro-democracy protests, killing hundreds and perhaps thousands of unarmed
civilians. Shots also were fired into the U.S. diplomatic
compound.
   The evacuation order expired last week, allowing the families to be
reunited.
   ``It's great to have her back,'' U.S. Ambassador James R. Lilley said
after his wife, Sally Booth Lilley, arrived on United
Airlines Flight 829 from Tokyo.
   ``The situation was judged calm enough to allow their return,'' Lilley
said. ``There's still alot of work to do in China-U.S
relations.''
   Families of other embassies, including the British Embassy and the
Australian Embassy, returned to China last month.
   Mrs. Lilley left Beijing about one month after arriving with her husband,
who took up his post as U.S. Ambassador to China on May
2.
   ``I'm happy 'cause I get to see my mother,'' said one young girl, whose
mother, an embassy official, remained in Beijing after
her family evacuated to the United States.
   Five American oil company employees also returned to Beijing on the
same flight en route to an oil field in remote Gansu province
in China's arid northwest.
   ``Yeh, we're glad to be back,'' said Pat Pyle of Carlsbad, N.M.
