<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Settlement     08-14 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Settlement,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Connecticut Stops Segregating Inmates With AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of Connecticut has settled a
federal lawsuit by agreeing to stop segregating inmates suffering
from AIDS.
   ``This consent decree reflects our new knowledge and
understanding of AIDS,'' Clarine Nardi Riddle, acting Connecticut
attorney general, said today.
   Judy Greenspan of the American Civil Liberties Union's national
prison project in Washington, praised the settlement as a landmark.
Attorneys said the settlement could affect similar lawsuits pending
in California and Alabama.
   ``By not segregating those with full-blown AIDS, Connecticut will
set an example for the rest of the country,'' Greenspan said.
   William Flower, a spokesman for the state prison system, said the
state stopped housing AIDS patients separately about six months ago
in response to the suit.
   Before that, inmates with AIDS symptoms were confined to an AIDS
ward for up to 23 hours a day at the maximum-security prison in
Somers. They were not allowed to take part in education, recreation
and religious programs.
   Under the settlement, there no longer will be a separate AIDS
ward, said Deborah Chang, an attorney for the inmates.
   Inmates' attorneys had charged that inmates put in the AIDS ward
with serious AIDS-related symptoms were kept there even after
showing improvement.
   ``The result was that a lot of people in the prison population
who were HIV-infected refused to go for treatment,'' said Chang.
   Five AIDS-infected inmates had brought the class-action lawsuit
against the state in 1988. Three of the inmates have since died.
   Flower said there is no reliable estimate of the number of
inmates infected with the AIDS virus. At last count, five were being
treated for AIDS-related illnesses in the system's acute care unit,
he said.
   But there is no mandatory testing for the virus, and some
officials have estimated that as many as 25 percent of the prison
system's 8,800 inmates carry the virus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890814-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Drugs-Thornburgh     08-14 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Thornburgh,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>War On Drugs Has Crippled Drug Traffickers, Thornburgh Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's six-year war on drugs
has made significant inroads in crippling and dismantling major drug
trafficking organizations, U.S. Attorney General Richard Thornburgh
said Monday.
   Thornburgh's comments were in stark opposition to those of Sen.
Joseph Biden, D-Del., who set out a nine-point drug program during
an emotional address here Sunday before the same congress of
correctional officers.
   Thornburgh said that since the drug enforcement task forces were
created in 1983, prosecutors have announced nearly 5,000 indictments
naming nearly 17,000 defendants.
   ``The striking results reflected in this annual report not only
underscore the effectiveness of this effort, but provide notice to
criminal organizations dealing in drugs that our resolve to destroy
them is unwavering,'' Thornburgh told the 119th congress of the
American Correctional Association.
   Biden told the corrections professionals that U.S. politicans
talk about waging a war against drug abuse but haven't shown the
courage of matching their rhetoric with the money to pay for
education and treatment.
   He warned that unless the war on drugs gets serious, the nation
faces disaster.
   ``It's now time for politicans, myself included, to stop talking
and start paying for what we say America needs to fight the drug
epidemic,'' said Biden, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   He blamed the lack of action on ``read my lips politics,'' a
pointed reference to President Bush's promise not to raise taxes.
Biden said Congress should instead ``read the lips of the American
people when they say, `Give us back our neighborhoods.'
   ``One thing is for sure, we have to get serious,'' Biden said.
``We have no war on drugs. We need a D-Day; we don't need another
Vietnam.''
   Biden outlined a program that emphasized drug treatment,
especially in prisons, research into cures for addiction and
education. He complained the nation was missing an opportunity to
break the ``drug-crime cycle'' because of the lack of drug treatment
programs in prisons.
   The drug problem is expected to be a major topic of discussion
throughout the five-day corrections conference.
</TEXT>
