<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSVaccine     08-14 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Vaccine,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Report Vaccine Protects Monkeys from AIDS Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTHBORO, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists today reported that an
experimental vaccine protected monkeys from the AIDS virus, but they
warned that the approach is unlikely to work in humans.
   Scientists from the New England Regional Primate Research Center
gave inactivated virus to six macaque monkeys. Two remained free of
infection when challenged with live virus. The others contracted the
virus but did not get sick.
   The researchers said theirs is the first published report
describing successful vaccine protection against infection by the
AIDS virus.
   ``At the very least, this vaccine seems to delay or prevent the
onset of disease symptoms,'' said Dr. Ronald C. Desrosiers, who
headed the team. ``In some cases, it seems to have even prevented
infection.''
   Their report was published in today's issue of the Proceedings of
the National Academy of Sciences.
   The scientists cautioned that the experiment was conducted under
carefully controlled laboratory conditions. The monkeys were
monitored extremely closely and challenged with virus when their
immune response from vaccination was the strongest.
   Desrosiers said that a human vaccine would have to elicit a more
powerful and sustained immune response.
   ``While we believe that this demonstrates that it is possible to
achieve some protection, a similar vaccine with the human virus is
not likely to be useful in humans,'' he said.
   The work was first presented in June at an AIDS meeting in
Montreal. At the meeting, researchers from the the University of
California, Davis, reported trying a similar approach in monkeys,
but their attempt failed to protect the animals from infection.
   Both experiments used vaccine made from inactivated simian
immunodeficiency virus, or SIV. This virus is a close relative of
HIV, the virus the causes AIDS in people.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
