<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--FairStabbing     08-14 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Fair Stabbing,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mental Patient Held Competent For Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mental patient accused of walking away
from a psychiatric hospital and stabbing to death a 9-year-old girl
at a street fair July 28 was found competent to stand trial today.
   Superior Court Judge Donald T. Dorsey accepted the unanimous
findings of an examining panel that David R. Peterson can understand
the charges and assist in his defense.
   At the same time, the panel found that Peterson was mentally ill
and had delusions of persecution.
   A hearing on the murder charges was set for Sept. 12.
   Police said that Peterson, 37, walked off the grounds of
Connecticut Valley Hospital, took a bus downtown, bought a hunting
knife and attacked Jessica Short at random in a crowd of hundreds.
She was stabbed repeatedly in the face and chest.
   Officials have since tightened security at state mental hospitals.
</TEXT>
