<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0538 08-14 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0538,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Drought Relief Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Insert 2 grafs of Dole, Yeutter comment after 7th graf, ``It
will''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, saying ``farmers have indeed
suffered,'' today signed legislation providing nearly $900 million
in disaster relief for farms where crops were battered this year by
rain, drought and other foul weather.
   In remarks at a signing ceremony, Bush said the Disaster
Assistance Act of 1989 brings ``important relief to farm families
hit by the extreme weather.''
   ``The farmer is at the mercy of the forces of nature, and
sometimes nature fails him,'' said the president, who persuaded
Congress to trim the relief package to $897 million from an earlier
$1.3 billion version passed by the House.
   ``This act will help farmers recover after damaging rain and wind
and will see others through a year when they've had to stand by and
watch their crops fail, Bush said.
   ``In a number of states from the Dakotas to the Texas Panhandle
and in the mid-Atlantic states as well, farmers have indeed
suffered, and this bill provides relief,'' he said. He also noted
that the winter wheat levels in Kansas were less than half normal
levels.
   ``The prevailing climate here in Washington is one of fiscal
restraint and money's tight. And that's why it is good news that the
cost of the disaster relief ... is reasonable,'' the president said.
   ``It will provide relief only to those farmers hardest hit by
adverse weather and it wisely rewards those who took the prudent
step of purchasing crop insurance,'' he said.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said later that $400
million of the new relief will go to wheat producers in his and
other states, who were hit the hardest.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said, ``We would much have
preferred to have a much more limited piece of legislation. And it
may work out, as a matter of fact, to be much limited in its
administration.''
   Farmers who participated in this year's price support program and
purchased crop insurance will be paid at 65 percent of the target
price for any losses beyond 35 percent of normal production.
   Those who were in the program but didn't buy crop insurance will
be compensated for losses beyond 40 percent of their normal
production. Those who were not in the program are eligible only if
their losses exceed 50 percent, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   Bush said he was also pleased that ``this law loosens some of the
controls that limit what farmers can plant, leaving more farmers
free then to choose the crops they grow and to diversify
agricultural production.''
   The president also was dispatching two aides with a congressional
delegation bound for Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, to bring back the
remains of Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and other Americans killed
in the crash of their mercy flight to a refugee camp. It was not
certain when the delegation would depart.
   Frederick McClure, the White House's top lobbyist, and a deputy,
Nicholas Calio, will join four members of Congress on the mission.
   Bush was informed at Camp David on Sunday that the wreckage had
been discovered on a remote hillside after an intense search. Bush
said in a statement that Leland and the others had died ``in a noble
cause _ trying to feed the hungry.''
   Later, after returning to the White House, Bush told reporters of
the ``profound sadness that we feel at the loss of the lives in
Ethiopia.''
   He said he had not yet spoken with the Texas congressman's widow,
Alison, ``but I certainly express my profound sadness, profound
regrets over all of this to her, and to their child.''
   He called the Houston congressman ``an outstanding man, a man of
great humor. Everyone from Texas knew of his lively nature and his
commitment to helping others.''
   With a smile, Bush recalled that both the Lelands had been his
guests ``in a happier time'' just 12 days earlier at a barbecue for
members of Congress on the South Lawn of the White House.
   Bush also conveyed his thanks to the government of Ethiopia and
to the U.S. military team that found the wreckage in what he called
``this almost unprecedented search.''
   The farm relief package is far less costly than the $4 billion
relief bill enacted during last year's drought. It will help farmers
still facing parched fields in parts of the Great Plans and western
Corn Belt, as well as farmers in parts of the South where flooding
wiped out rice and cotton crops.
   To qualify for relief, farmers in the government subsidy program
for corn, wheat, cotton, tobacco, peanuts and sugar must suffer a 40
percent crop loss. The threshold will be 45 percent for soybean and
sunflower growers and 50 percent for fruit and vegetable farmers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
