<FIRST>u w PM-DrugPoll 2ndLd-Writethru a0568 08-14 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Poll, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0568,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls Show Anti-Drug Supporter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds one graf with sampling error</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-fourths of all teen-agers and nearly half
of all adults are ready to volunteer time to drug prevention
programs, education and treatment and 9 in 10 Americans want tougher
anti-drug laws, a new Gallup poll showed today.
   ``The American people are in a wartime mode,'' said George Gallup
in a White House news conference.
   William Bennett, the national drug control director who will make
the Bush Administration's policy public early next month, said ``the
American people have given a very clear sense of direction to us,''
in the poll.
   ``The public is ready to take action on all fronts,'' he said.
   The survey showed that drug abuse was listed by 32 percent of
teen-agers as the most important problem facing the country, ahead
of fear of war, 14 percent;, economic issues, 13 percent;
environment and pollution, 7 percent; AIDS, 5 percent; crime, 3
percent; and abortion, 2 percent.
   Bennett said he didn't want to disclose the administration's new
policy prematurely but said ``if there is a subtitle to our
strategy, it is everybody plays. Everybody must do something.''
   Gallup interviewed 1,005 adults and 500 teen-agers in June and
July in what he said was the first project of the newly formed
Gallup International Foundation.
   ``A record number of Americans cite the drug crisis as the
nation's top problem, replacing the `guns and butter' issues of
international tensions and economic worries,'' he said. ``In the 50
years that the U.S. public has been asked to name the most important
problem facing the nation, it is virtually unprecedented for any
social issue to appear at the top of the list.''
   He said 75 percent of teens and 48 percent of adults said they
would be willing to work in drug programs and while there is a gap
between what people say and what they will do, ``it is clear there
are enormous numbers of Americans waiting to be mobilized in the war
on drugs.''
   The margin of error was given as four percentage points for the
adults questioned and six percentage points for the smaller group of
teens surveyed.
</TEXT>
