<HEAD>American's Appeal Against Extradition To U.S. Refused</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court on Monday rejected an
appeal by an American who sought to block his extradition to the
United States to face charges of attempted murder and arson, the
national news agency Itim said.
   Joel Davis of Silver Spring, Md., was accused in a U.S. court in
Baltimore in 1985 of hiring three men to kill an Internal Revenue
Service agent to block an investigation into Davis' financial
affairs, Itim said.
   Davis, 47, was also accused of paying $15,000 to burn down a
vacation village known as Torah Town that he owned in New York, in
an attempt to collect fire insurance, the news agency said.
   Davis reportedly fled to Israel shortly after he was indicted,
and his extradition was requested in 1987 after U.S. officials
discovered him in Jerusalem.
   A Jerusalem District Court ordered his extradition last year, but
Davis appealed to the Supreme Court.
