<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-Sullivan     08-14 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Sullivan,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan, Citing New Treatments, Urges More Voluntary AIDS Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Louis Sullivan on Monday said
the success of new treatments should encourage more people to be
tested for AIDS, though he offered no assurance these therapies
would be available to those who cannot afford them.
   Sullivan also said the government and local communities must do a
better job targeting AIDS prevention messages to minorities, and he
said people with AIDS must not be treated as ``political footballs.''
   Speaking at the opening session of a national conference on AIDS
among racial and ethnic populations, the secretary noted that the
disease is taking a disproportionate toll on the minority community.
   Blacks, who comprise 12 of the U.S. population, represent 26
percent of adult AIDS cases in the United States and 53 percent of
pediatric cases, he said. Hispanics, who make up 7 percent of the
nation's population, represent 15 percent of adult cases and 23
percent of pediatric cases.
   ``We must increasingly develop accurate and credible information
campaigns that will successfully reach and motivate Americans who
have been missed by our previous efforts,'' Sullivan said. ``That
means we must develop culturally relevant and sensitive materials
that can be carefully targeted to an identified group.''
   However, he added, ``community standards must be respected'' in
messages designed to educate about the disease that is often
transmitted through sexual contact.
   Homosexual and bisexual men comprise 62 percent of the nation's
AIDS cases, though intravenous drug users who now represent 20
percent of the cases are the fastest growing segment of people with
the disease.
   Sullivan said the epidemic must remain focused on public health,
with no judgments about morality.
   ``People with AIDS must not be treated as bargaining chips or
political footballs. They must be given our compassion, our respect
and our best efforts,'' he said.
   He added: ``We must end the specter of discrimination.''
   As of July 30, The total number of Americans diagnosed with AIDS
reached 102,621, of whom 59,391 have died since July 1, 1981,
according to the Centers for Disease Control.
   Between 1 million and 1.5 million Americans are believed to be
infected with the virus, though many of them do not know it because
they have never been tested, Sullivan said.
   With new therapies being approved to treat the disease in its
early states and prolong survival, more people should be pursuaded
to get tested, he said.
   Asked in a brief session with reporters after his address how the
government plans to make these therapies available to those who test
positive but cannot pay for the treatments, he offered little
assurance.
   ``The federal role is not the sole responsibility for addressing
this problem,'' he said. ``Certainly state governments and local
governments as well as private insurance also have a role to play.
   ``The picture is one we're constantly evaluating, and if we find
we're falling short within an area we know we can do better, we're
going to be seeking those additional funds,'' he said.
   He said President Bush's proposed fiscal 1990 budget did not
include any money for early intervention treatments because when the
spending plan was drafted, the therapies now proving successful were
not known to be effective. He said he was ``looking to Congress to
address that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
