<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1440EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     08-14 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Team to Visit Cambodian Guerrilla Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. team working on a Cambodian peace
plan arrived Monday to visit guerrilla bases on the Thai side of the
border.
   The 15-member group, mostly military specialists, spent a week in
Cambodia to determine what would be needed to form an international
body to monitor a Vietnamese troop pullout and a truce.
   The team inspected the country's transport and communications,
and visited the Vietnamese border.
   ``We were able to see as much as we could in the days we were in
Cambodia,'' the team's leader, Lt. Gen. Martin O. Vadset of Norway,
said in Bangkok. ``It is difficult to cover every square meter of
any country, and the infrastructure in Cambodia implies that you
cannot move as fast as you could, even if you use helicopters.''
   Vadset said his team plans to meet with Foreign Minister Siddi
Savetsila of Thailand and representatives of the three Cambodian
guerrilla factions.
   Maj. Gen. Amporn Chuataputhi, Thai liaison officer for the U.N.
team, said the team would start Tuesday by visiting a northern base
controlled by forces of the joint resistance leader Prince Sihanouk.
   The group plans to travel to a camp of the Khmer People's
National Liberation Front on Wednesday and an area controlled by the
Khmer Rouge on Thursday.
   The Communist Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of people
when it ruled Cambodia for nearly four years. Vietnam invaded in
late 1978, driving out the Khmer Rouge and installing another
Communist government.
   Jamshid Anvar, the U.N. team's political adviser, said the visit
to the resistance's military bases would be the first official one
by the United Nations.
   The Vietnamese pullout of 26,000 troops from Cambodia, announced
for late September, will leave the Vietnamese-installed government
in Phnom Penh fighting the guerrilla coalition unless international
peace talks in Paris take a dramatic turnaround.
   Nations at the talks sent the U.N. team to the region to help in
their efforts to prepare a settlement. The team plans to leave for
Paris on Sunday and report back to the conference.
   One team member, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it may
require 120 personnel to monitor the pullout and about 6,000 to form
a peacekeeping force. The effort would cost hundreds of millions of
dollars and probably could not be organized outside U.N. auspices,
he said.
   The prime minister of the pro-Vietnamese government, Hun Sen, has
opposed a peacekeeping force and a U.N. role in the peace process.
</TEXT>
