<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1441EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DisabledChildren     08-14 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabled Children,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Proposes New Eligibility Rules for Disabled Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Monday proposed revised rules
for determining which children have mental impairments that make
them eligible for disability payments under the Supplemental
Security Income program.
   The Department of Health and Human Services said the proposed
changes would provide more explicit methods for evaluating childhood
impairments including chronic brain syndrome, psychotic disorders
and mental retardation.
   HHS Secretary Louis W. Sullivan said the changes ``will assure
that our decision-making process keeps pace with the advances in
medical knowledge in the mental health field.''
   Social Security spokesman Phil Gambino said the changes, which
are subject to public comment for 60 days, could result in a slight
increase in the number of children who qualify for disability
payments.
   More than 250,000 children receive SSI benefits, almost half of
whom are mentally impaired.
   SSI, administered by the Social Security Administration, provides
a minimal income floor for the nation's aged, disabled and blind.
Maximum benefits are $368 a month.
</TEXT>
