<FIRST>u p AM-TexasGovernor 1stLd-Writethru a0577 08-14 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Governor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0577,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy's Slow, but Spending's Not for Aspiring Governors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Besides Maddox...', to CORRECT spelling of Mattox.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AT12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil's down, real estate's reeling and banks
are in the red. But politicians aren't letting that crimp their
big-spending style in the race to replace multimillionaire oilman
Bill Clements as governor.
   Political analysts are predicting a big-spending free-for-all
next year in the first race in more than 20 years in which an
incumbent Texas governor isn't seeking re-election.
   Democratic Attorney General Jim Mattox, who has collected more
than $4 million for his expected campaign, disagreed with a recent
newspaper report that suggested gubernatorial spending could hit $50
million.
   ``I think that's way too low,'' he said.
   GOP candidate Jack Rains, a former Texas secretary of state and
founder of the 3D International engineering and design firm, put it
another way:
   ``I am prepared to stand toe-to-toe and wad up dollar bills and
start throwing them,'' Rains said. ``They're going to run out of
money before all of my friends and I do.''
   Besides Mattox and Rains, the lineup of people planning or
considering bids for Clements' office includes a rising national
Democratic star, a pair of comeback minded ex-governors, a
millionaire oilman and rancher, a Democrat-turned-Republican, and
corporate raider T. Boone Pickens.
   But it doesn't include President Bush's eldest son, George W.
Bush of Dallas, co-owner of the Texas Rangers baseball team.
Although many Republicans said he would be the front-runner, Bush
bowed out Aug. 1, saying the only race he cares about is for the
American League pennant.
   Clements, the state's only Republican governor this century, had
announced shortly after winning his second term that he didn't
intend to seek a third. He'll be 73 when the term expires in January
1991. The last incumbent to voluntarily step down was John Connally
in 1968.
   In the wake of Republican inroads in Texas, Democratic national
Chairman Ron Brown recently said the state is crucial to party hopes
for the 1990s. He noted that no Democrat has been elected president
this century without carrying Texas, and added, ``We have got to
recapture the statehouse here.''
   But that's a costly proposition in a state that spans two time
zones and has more than 20 television markets. The 1986 race, for
example, saw combined spending by Clements and then-Gov. Mark White
of about $25 million though both had little opposition.
   While the primary isn't until March 1990, candidates in both
parties have been jockeying for months. Only three have formally
declared, but a fourth is ready to do so Tuesday and others are
raising money or admit to ``considering'' a race.
   State Treasurer Ann Richards is the only announced Democratic
candidate. She became an instant celebrity after her 1988 Democratic
National Convention keynote speech accusing President Bush of being
``born with a silver foot in his mouth.'' She has banked more than
$1 million and favors abortion rights and more action to help the
environment.
   Three other Democrats are considering a run:
   _ Mattox. Except for his first try for party precinct chairman,
he has never lost a race for public office. The former congressman
compiled an activist record on consumer fraud, nursing home abuse
and environmental issues.
   _ White. He ousted Clements in 1982, only to be ousted in return
in 1986. Now a lawyer in Houston, White says he'll decide by fall
whether to try a Clements-style comeback.
   _ Dolph Briscoe, who was elected governor in 1972 and lost the
Democratic primary in 1978. The 65-year-old multimillionaire rancher
and banker says there is a vacuum of conservative leadership in the
party.
   There are two announced Republican candidates and a third set to
make his formal announcement this week:
   _ Clayton Williams, oilman, rancher, telephone company founder,
who pledged to spend $3 million of his own to win the Republican
nomination. But his start was a little rocky when news reports noted
that Williams contributed to two Democratic potential rivals, Mattox
and Ms. Richards, last year.
   _ Rains. He was campaign strategist for Clements, who appointed
him secretary of state, the state's top political patronage job, in
1987. He quit the post when he launched his gubernatorial bid.
   _ Kent Hance, who is planning his formal announcement Tuesday. A
one-time Democratic congressman from Lubbock, he lost the 1984
Democratic nomination for Senate, then changed parties. His 1986 bid
for governor failed, but he has since become a member of the
powerful Railroad Commission, which regulates oil and gas production.
   In addition, oilman Pickens, who has staged takeover battles of
such well-known companies as Phillips Petroleum, is reportedly
looking for a new house in Dallas' Republican strongholds and has
said he will decide soon whether to seek a different type of chief
executive's chair.
</TEXT>
