<FIRST>r a AM-MineDeaths     08-14 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mine Deaths,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>3 Teens Die While Exploring Abandoned Mine; Gas Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of teen-agers exploring an
abandoned coal mine apparently were overcome by poison gas, and
three were killed, authorities said Monday.
   A fourth youth rescued from the mine was hospitalized in serious
condition.
   The fifth member of the group walked and ran more than five miles
through rugged desert to get help for his friends after they
collapsed late Sunday, said Mesa County Sheriff's Lt. Wayne Harms.
   Miles Slape, 17, the boy who went for help, reported he had
trouble breathing in the mine, and investigators believed the
teen-agers were poisoned by some kind of gas, Harms said. Autopsies
were ordered.
   ``Those old mines have all kinds of gas, the older the mine the
more gas they have,'' Harms said. ``They're very, very dangerous
things.''
   Killed were two girls _ Christian Rossman, 15, and Catherine
Schrettner, 16 _ and a boy, Greg Folchert, 17. Frank Warner, 16, was
listed in stable but serious condition Monday at St. Mary's
Hostpital in Grand Junction.
   Slape was unhurt, Harms said. He had to go on foot because he
didn't have keys to the car.
   The abandoned Carpenter Mine is northeast of Grand Junction in
eastern Colorado.
   The teen-agers hiked to the mine sometime late Sunday, Harms
said. Slape entered first, but came out to tell his friends he had
trouble breathing$
   ``They didn't believe him so they went in and never came back
out,'' Harms said.
   Slape got worried and went back in the mine but found he couldn't
help his friends, Harms said. He ran for help, and rescuers arrived
at the mine about 11:30 p.m. to find the teen-agers dead inside.
</TEXT>
