<HEAD>Judge Grants Temporary Restraining Order In HUD Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday issued a temporary
restraining order that prevents Hartford from awarding a disputed
$1.5 million rent subsidy contract, an attorney said.
   Judge Jose A. Cabranes also set a hearing Wednesday on a lawsuit
filed by Hartconn Associates Inc. of Bridgeport last week against
the city, according to attorney Sue Wise, who represents Hartconn.
   Hartconn claims it lost out on the contract to manage Hartford's
rent subsidy program because its competition, Imagineers Inc., had
better ties to Hartford politicians. The contract was awarded to
Imagineers in July. Imagineers has run the city's Section 8 program
for 13 years.
   Arthur Anderson, president of Imagineers, said last week that
politics played no role in the awarding of the contract and called
the charges ``baloney.''
   Wise said the restraining order would not interfere with the
services provided by the subsidy program.
