<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-14 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Issue Subpoena for Opposition Leader in Spy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Monday they have
obtained a subpoena to question opposition leader Kim Dae-jung in
connection with charges that two members of his party spied for
North Korea.
   Kim angrily denied any wrongdoing and said he would comply with
the subpoena to prove his innocence.
   He said his Party for Peace and Democracy has declared political
war on the government of President Roh Tae-woo, which he said was
out to destroy the country's leading opposition.
   ``Our party efforts to cooperate with the regime of President Roh
Tae-woo are over,'' Kim said. ``There can be no dialogue with people
out to destroy us.''
   Prosecutors said Kim would be asked to appear for questioning
Aug. 22 in connection with a secret three-day visit to communist
North Korea by party lawmaker Suh Kyung-won in August 1988.
   Suh, 52, and an aide, Pang Yang-kyun, 34, were indicted Saturday
on charges of being North Korean agents. If convicted, they face
life imprisonment.
   Prosecutors quoted Suh as confessing he had received $50,000
after meeting with North Korean President Kim Il Sung and had given
$10,000 to the party leader after returning to Seoul.
   They also quoted Suh as confessing that he reported back in
mid-April to Kim Dae-jung about his secret trip. That would be two
months earlier than Kim said he was informed of the trip.
   ``I never received a penny of money from him,'' Kim said. ``The
prosecutors' disclosures are 100 percent untrue. He never told me
anything of a secret trip to North Korea.''
   Kim has never denied Suh made the illegal trip. However, he says
his party was not involved and he knew nothing about it until Suh
informed party officials shortly before turning himself in June 25.
   The party leader said he was asking Amnesty International and the
Human Rights Institute in Washington to investigate charges the
South Korean intelligence agency and prosecutors were trying to
discredit the opposition.
   A subpoena also was issued for the party's former floor leader,
Kim Won-kie. Prosecutors said he also knew of Suh's trip in April
but failed to report it as required by law.
   Kim Dae-jung, who was defeated in presidential elections in 1971
and 1987, was questioned by government investigators last week about
whether he knew of Suh's trip in advance or sent a secret message to
North Korean leaders through Suh or other channels.
   After the 22-hour interrogation, Kim said he had been cleared of
all allegations involving him, but officials said their inquiry was
incomplete and would continue.
   Pro-Western South Korea only allows authorized visits to North
Korea, its bitter enemy since the peninsula was divided at the end
of the Korean War.
   Also on Monday, the official North Korea news agency said a
dissident South Korea student planned to try again Tuesday to cross
the border at Panmunjom to return home after an illegal trip to
North Korea.
   The Korean Central News Agency, monitored in Tokyo, said the
Pyongyang government had again asked that U.N. officials stationed
at the border allow Im Su-kyong to cross. The U.N. Command has said
the nations must work out the dispute.
   Ms. Im, who has said she wants to make her trip a symbolic act
for reunification, originally planned to cross on July 27, but she
says South Korean officials refused.
   The 20-year-old student traveled to North Korea via Japan and
East Germany for an international youth festival July 1-8. She faces
arrest upon her return. Also Monday, the Rev. Allan Boesak of South
Africa told delegates to an international church conference in Seoul
that they should work for reunification.
   ``Supporting the reconciliation and reunification of Korea is a
catchy phrase, but we need to call for action,'' he said at the
conference of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   Boesak, a prominent critic of the South African government and
president of the alliance, also said the delegates should ``pay
special attention'' to the cases of Ms. Im and a clergyman on trial
for an illegal trip to North Korea.
</TEXT>
