<SECOND>AM-BRF--Berlin-US,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Man Enters East Berlin, is Sent Back by Guards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American man who once pounded on the Berlin Wall
with a jackhammer and staged other protests at the barrier on Monday
entered East Berlin with Western newspapers but was quickly sent
back by East German guards.
   John Runnings of Seattle apparently intended to distribute
Western newspapers in East Berlin, where they are not available.
   But as soon as Runnings, 71, crossed into East Berlin through
Checkpoint Charlie, he was picked up by East German guards.
   Shortly afterward, reporters on the Western side saw Runnings
being picked up by a West Berlin ambulance and returned to West
Berlin. It was not immediately clear if Runnings had been injured.
   Runnings has carried out a one-man campaign against the wall for
several years.
   He had been given an 18-month suspended sentence by an East
Berlin court after he had climbed atop the wall in 1987.
   Runnings' latest action came one day after several protests on
the Western side to mark the 28th anniversary of the construction of
the Berlin Wall by the communists.
