<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 4thLd-Writethru   08-14 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0599,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prime Minister to Resign</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to ADD comments from Peasant Party spokesman, other
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak said today
he will give up his bid to form a new government and resign so the
leader of the small United Peasant Party can take over and form a
coalition government.
   His announcement, broadcast by the state-run PAP news agency,
came as Solidarity tried to persuade the Peasants, aligned with the
Communists in Parliament, to join in a non-communist coalition.
   ``At the moment, a situation has been created in which I can see
a chance to form a new government by (Peasant leader) Roman
Malinowski in which there would be representatives of all forces
represented at the Parliament,'' Kiszczak said in a statement issued
by PAP.
   Kiszczak was elected prime minister Aug. 2, winning a majority in
Parliament despite objections from the Solidarity caucus, which
holds 35 percent of Parliament's seats.
   Solidarity's Parliament leader, Bronislaw Geremek, refused
comment on Kiszczak's announcement. Solidarity leader Lech Walesa
was not at home and could not be reached for comment.
   Walesa said last week that Solidarity could not support a
government formed by Kiszczak, and he invited the Peasant Party and
the Democratic Party, also aligned with the Communists, to join in a
coalition. That would give Poland its first non-communist government
since World War II.
   Earlier today, Walesa tried to arrange talks with Malinowski and
Jerzy Jozwiak, the leader of the Democratic Party, but the two
leaders apparently declined to meet with him.
   Kiszczak said Walesa's proposal ``complicates and prolongs the
process'' of trying to form a government.
   But he said the proposal also indicated Walesa's negative
attitude toward a coalition government had eased, creating a chance
for a ``grand coalition'' in which the opposition would be offered
several ministries.
   Kiszczak said he viewed Malinowski as having the best chance of
forming such a coalition.
   Solidarity has rejected the ``grand coalition'' idea, saying the
new government must have public support to rule and that a
Communist-led coalition would not have such support.
   Kiszczak said he would contact President Wojciech Jaruzelski ``so
that he considers the new situation and draws from it the proper
conclusions.''
   The speaker of the Parliament, Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, said
Jaruzelski must accept Kiszczak's resignation. He said the
Parliament would then have to vote on Malinowski if he were formally
nominated.
   However, Aleksander Bentkowski, the Peasant Party parliamentary
caucus leader, said in a telephone interview he was not sure
Malinowski would accept the nomination because of the slim chances
of successfully forming a coalition.
   Malinowski, 54, has led the Peasant Party since 1981, but he was
among the prominent Communist coalition candidates who failed to win
election in June.
   In the June 4 elections, Solidarity-backed candidates won all 161
seats open to them in the 460-member Sejm, or Parliament, and 99 of
100 seats in the newly created Senate.
   The Communists control 37 percent of the Parliament and
Solidarity has 35 percent. The Peasant Party and Democratic Party
hold the balance of parliamentary power.
   Earlier today, Solidarity Senator Jaroslaw Kaczynski read a brief
statement from Walesa in which he said his offer of a coalition with
the Peasants and Democrats stood.
   Kaczynski confirmed Sunday that Walesa himself was considering
being prime minister in a Solidarity-led coalition government.
   Kaczynski began talks with the two minor parties Thursday and
they continued through the weekend at an undisclosed site, he said.
</TEXT>
