<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Shuttle-Condition     08-14 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Condition,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Says Columbia in Good Shape After Military Flight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot's seat on
Columbia jerked backward about one inch when the space shuttle was
launched last week, but the malfunction caused no problems, a NASA
official said today.
   ``It was exciting when it happened,'' but shuttle pilot Richard
Richards used a motor control to move the seat forward to its normal
position ``and it stayed,'' said Ann Montgomery, in charge of
processing Columbia after its five-day military mission.
   The shuttle's commander and pilot actually do very little during
liftoff, which is almost entirely controlled by computers.
   A leaky in-flight steering thruster will need replacing, but
Columbia's crew shut it down during the flight and used other
thrusters, Montgomery said.
   Only three of the shuttle's roughly 30,000 heat-shielding tiles
were damaged enough to require replacement, based on initial
inspection, she said. Two of the tiles may have been damaged when
yet-unidentified debris fell from the shuttle when it was launched
Tuesday from Florida, she added.
   Overall, Columbia ``looks absolutely beautiful,'' Montgomery
said, adding that workers will examine about 20 other minor
potential problems that developed just before or during Columbia's
flight.
   The shuttle landed at this Mojave Desert military base Sunday
morning after its five-day, one-hour mission to deploy a satellite,
which experts have said is a modified KH-12 spy satellite designed
to photograph military targets. The astronauts also reportedly
performed experiments related to the ``Star Wars'' anti-missile
defense system.
   Columbia probably will leave Saturday for a piggyback flight back
to Cape Canaveral, Fla., atop a modified Boeing 747 jetliner,
Montgomery said.
   Columbia's mission restored the shuttle fleet to three orbiters.
Columbia is the oldest shuttle. It last flew in January 1986,
landing 10 days before Challenger exploded during liftoff, killing
seven crew members. After the accident NASA concentrated on making
safety modifications to the two newer shuttles, Discovery and
Atlantis, before refurbishing Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
