<DOCNO> AP890814-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1611EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Trucker'sDeath     08-14 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trucker's Death,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indiana Man Found Dead After Nine Days in Parked Truck</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a trucker was found in a
tractor-trailer rig that sat _ with engine running _ in a parking
lot for nine days, authorities said Monday.
   Lester Peters, 55, of Laurel, Ind., apparently died of carbon
monoxide poisoning, said Joseph Inman, an investigator with the
Lucas County coroner's office.
   No foul play was suspected, Inman said, adding it appeared the
driver fell asleep. An autopsy was planned.
   Peters' decomposed body was found by police Sunday afternoon in
the cab of his tractor-trailor, which had been parked with its
engine running since Aug. 4 in the parking lot of a McDonald's on
the city's north side.
   The truck had enough fuel _ about 200 gallons _ to run for two
weeks. Inman said he didn't know why somebody didn't call police
until Sunday afternoon.
   ``Apparently they swept the parking lot around it. ... I have no
idea why. You would think someone would notice a truck in the
parking lot with its engine running,'' he said.
   The McDonald's manager didn't respond Monday to a telephone
request for comment.
   Peters, who was working for TMC Trucking Co. of Des Moines, Iowa,
picked up a shipment of steel at Heidtman Steel Products, about 1{
miles from the McDonald's, on Aug. 4. He was to take the shipment to
Greenup, Ill., and was expected to arrive Aug. 7, Inman said.
   On Aug. 9, the trucking company notified Peters' wife, Janice,
that he was missing. The family called the police and then launched
its own search of truck stops and rest areas along his planned
route, said Peters' sister, Shirley Combs of Connersville, Ind.
   ``They went everywhere where they thought he might be on the
road, somewhere. They took his picture and posted them in truck
stops and rest areas,'' Ms. Combs said.
   She said said her brother was going to quit his job and start a
truck repair shop. He had been working seven days a week over the
last few months to pay off his new truck and to open the shop.
   She said she found it hard to believe no one called police about
the truck.
   ``People nowadays are just in too big of a rush. They just don't
pay attention to one another,'' she said.
</TEXT>
