<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1539EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Ethiopia-Leland 1stLd-Writethru a0565 08-14 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Leland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Delays Recovery of Bodies By One Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs ``The four ...'' to UPDATE
with State Department saying it will take at least two days to recover
bodies; picks up 9th graf pvs ``Haley said ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Smith-Plane, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bad weather stalled efforts Monday
to recover the bodies of Rep. Mickey Leland and 15 companions from a
mountain ravine in remote southwestern Ethiopia, where their plane
crashed a week ago.
   Heavy clouds and rain forced two Blackhawk helicopters carrying
recovery teams to return to the capital twice before the weather
cleared enough for them to make the 250-mile flight to the crash
site in midafternoon.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman James Haley said they arrived too late to
begin full-scale recovery operations Monday.
   ``We've got people down there and have started taking the
necessary photographs, but we won't begin retrieving bodies until
tomorrow,'' he said.
   Leland, a 44-year-old Texas Democrat who headed the House Select
Committee on Hunger, was on his fifth visit to Africa and his second
this year.
   His chartered plane crashed Aug. 7 en route to Fugnido, one of
four camps in southwestern Ethiopia run by the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees. They house more than 300,000 Sudanese who
have fled war and famine in the neighboring country.
   Twelve bodies were found Sunday on the slopes of a mountain where
the Twin Otter crashed on the way to Fugnido, about 350 miles
southwest of Addis Ababa. The small, twin-engine plane apparently
hit a cliff about 1,200 feet below the summit of the 5,500-foot
mountain in bad weather.
   The four missing bodies were believed to be in the wreckage.
Bodies and parts of the plane were strewn over a wide area of the
barely accessible slope, to which searchers had to be lowered from
helicopters on Sunday.
   In Washington, the State Department said Monday that recovery of
the bodies will require at least two days of good weather.
   ``Officials on the scene believe that the recovery will be a slow
and laborious process because of the weather, the rough terrain, and
the steep incline of the slope where the wreckage is located,'' said
spokesman Richard Boucher. He said the wreckage was on a 70-degree
slope.
   Boucher also said Ethiopia has accepted an offer from the U.S.
National Transportation Safety Board to investigate the cause of the
crash. He said a team from the NTSB was en route to Ethiopia.
   Haley said the two Blackhawk helicopters would stay overnight at
Gambela, 35 miles southeast of the crash site, and begin retrieval
operations at daybreak. He said they would be joined by two more
Blackhawks with rescue teams, and two C-130 cargo planes carrying
helicopter fuel would leave for the area at dawn.
   After being taken by helicopter to nearby Dembidola village, the
bodies are to be flown by a C-130 to Addis Ababa. Nine Americans and
seven Ethiopians were on the Leland plane.
   The bodies of the Americans are expected to be taken to the
United States later this week on a C-141 hospital plane sent to
Ethiopia last week, according to Navy Capt. Stan Bloyer in
Washington.
   Bloyer said a four-member congressional delegation planned to fly
to Ethiopia to escort the bodies home but would not leave Washington
until the remains had been identified.
   Reps. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., Al Wheat, D-Mo., and the
sergeant-at-arms of the House of Representatives, Jack Russ, left
Ethiopia on Monday, Haley said. They had arrived Friday to observe
the search operation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
