<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories 1stLd-Writethru a0580 08-14 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Rise, Sales Dip in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of ``economist'' in grafs 3 and 5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in June
as business sales fell 0.3 percent, the government said Monday.
Analysts said the report was in line with the economic
``soft-landing'' sought by the Federal Reserve Board _ slow but
continued growth with low inflation.
   Inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as
production exceeds demand, a process that sometimes leads to a loss
of jobs as businesses cut their output.
   Economists, however, said recent inventory-to-sales ratios are
not unusually high.
   ``Inventories are not out of hand yet,'' said Howard Roth of
Security Pacific National Bank in Los Angeles.
   ``The basic message is that inventory vulnerability is fairly
limited in the economy,'' commented Robert G. Dederick, chief
economist for The Northern Trust Co. of Chicago. ``This suggests
that the prospect of an outright recession is limited.''
   Inventories held on shelves and backlots climbed to a seasonally
adjusted $780.8 billion in June, the Commerce Department said. The
0.4 percent jump followed increases of 0.9 percent in May and 0.8
percent in April.
   Business sales, meanwhile, fell 0.3 percent to a seasonally
adjusted $516.4 billion after rising 0.1 percent in May and 2
percent in April, the department said. Sales had last fallen in
February, when they were down 0.9 percent.
   The June report was consistent with recent indicators that
economic growth had slowed as the Federal Reserve tightened credit
to restrain inflation.
   In a report Friday, the Labor Department said wholesale prices
one step short of retail had fallen 0.4 percent in July, their
biggest decline in three years. At the same time, the Commerce
Department reported that retail sales in July had risen a strong 0.9
percent after falling 0.1 percent in June.
   Roth said the July retail sales report means ``we'll probably
have pretty strong (business) sales in next report. As far as the
economy is concerned, it looks like the soft-landing scenario is
still pretty good.''
   Monday's business sales report includes transactions at three
levels _ manufacturing, wholesale and retail.
   The ratio of inventories to sales in June was 1.51, meaning it
would take 1.51 months to exhaust inventories at the June sales
pace. The ratio had stood at 1.50 in May and 1.49 in April
   Manufacturers' inventories, which represent 47 percent of the
total, rose 0.3 percent, while retailers' stocks were up 0.6
percent. Wholesalers registered a 0.1 percent increase.
   Total inventories were 8.2 percent higher than in June 1988.
   Manufacturers' sales, on the other hand, fell 0.5 percent.
Wholesalers' sales were off 0.3 percent while retailers' sales were
down 0.1 percent.
   Overall, sales were up 6.2 percent from a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
