<FIRST>r a AM-NoPrincipal     08-14 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-No Principal,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Tries Going Without Principal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILL CITY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There hasn't been a principal running the
Hill City school since last year, and the district is not even
looking for one.
   A committee of teachers runs the school, with supervision from
the district superintendent, as part of a three-year experiment that
takes teacher-power to a new level.
   The idea of giving more power to teachers, sometimes known as
site-based management or shared decision-making, is being widely
advocated by school reformers, and rural schools have been known to
share or do without a principal to save money. But only one other
district in Minnesota has gone as far as Hill City in letting
teachers run a school outright.
   ``It's not perfect, but ... I think if you were to go in the
building and ask if morale is better, they'd say yes,'' said Linda
Bauer, a counselor and teacher on Hill City's ``share team.''
   ``People here have the chance to express their opinions and
views. We use the strengths of all people on the staff _ bus
drivers, cooks, people who have a unique perspective on what's going
on in a student's life.''
   Hill City's school has about 330 students in kindergarten to
grade 12. The ``share team,'' about to begin its second year of
managing the school, has two elementary teachers, two secondary
teachers and the school secretary. Teachers are paid roughly $4,400
extra for the team work.
   Last year, the team met daily for about 45 minutes before school
and had regular weekly meetings lasting about 2{ hours. The
secretary made many decisions about such things as office supplies,
and one team member was free each day to function as a
quasi-principal.
   Not everyone in this north-central Minnesota community of 360,
and the rural area around it that also sends children to its school,
has been happy with the experiment. Vernon Bishop, a new school
board member, said parents have been frustrated with the lack of a
principal and some believe the system jeopardizes confidentiality.
   ``I'm willing to give this a chance,'' he said. ``(But) for
parents I have talked to, it's a real big concern.''
   Superintendent Darrell Nelson said some parents don't like the
fact that substitute teachers fill in for the team members when they
are doing management duties.
   Richard Mesenberg, manager of the state Department of Education's
Office of Educational Leadership, says he doesn't recommend the Hill
City system because sometimes committees can't make decisions.
   But in general, Mesenberg said, parent and teacher involvement in
school decisions is the first part of a long-term change in American
education. ``We're making schools fundamentally different than they
were yesterday,'' he said.
   State officials estimate 25 to 30 of Minnesota's 435 school
districts are seriously involved in some form of decentralized
management.
   ``There is no model, and that frustrates people,'' said Ted Suss,
administrator for the State Board of Education. But fostering a
model for local schools to follow would undo the very reason for
decentralization in the first place, he said.
   Two of the state's biggest school districts, Minneapolis and St.
Paul, are set to begin organized efforts this fall to give schools
more local control. Winona, enrollment 4,600, has one of the state's
oldest programs. The district's 10 regular schools have had ``school
site councils'' with teachers and principals for five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890814-0113 </DOCNO>
