<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-14 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Call for General Strike, 14 Killed in Strife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists called for a
one-day general strike Tuesday to demand withdrawal of Indian
peacekeeping soldiers.
   Military officials said Monday that 14 more people were killed in
the island's ethnic violence.
   The killings were reported around central and southern Sri Lanka,
where members of the majority ethnic Sinhalese dominate, on Sunday
and Monday, military officials said.
   The strike was called to coincide with India's independence day.
The anti-government People's Liberation Front announced the strike
through posters and leaflets in the capital and its suburbs.
   The Sinhalese-language posters warned people to stay indoors.
Several earlier strikes called by the front have been largely
successful.
   Monday's posters denounced the presence of an estimated 43,000
Indian soldiers.
   The soldiers were deployed in the northeast to oversee a 1987
peace accord that aimed to end an ethnic Tamil insurrection for an
independent nation.
   The ultra-nationalist front says the presence of Indian troops
compromises the country's sovereignty. It also says the government
is making too many concessions to the Tamil militants, who began
their separatist campaign in 1983.
   The Tamils say they suffer discrimination from Sinhalese, who
make up 75 percent of the population.Tamils comprise 18 percent of
Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has asked India to withdraw its
soldiers, but the results have failed to appease the extremists.
   India has pulled out 2,220 soldiers since Premadasa made the
request June 1 but says a quick withdrawal of all troops could lead
to more violence.
   Instead, it has said it will withdraw its soldiers in phases,
pulling them all out by February.
   The government accuses the front of killing at least 4,000 people
during the last two years. About 11,000 other people have died in
the 6-year-old Tamil revolt.
   With the latest killings, the toll in the extremist violence
since Saturday rose to 72, the military officials said.
</TEXT>
