<FIRST>r i AM-Opera-Defectors     08-14 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera-Defectors,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Members of East German Opera Reportedly Defect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six members of East Germany's leading opera company
have defected in London after a two-week tour and are expected to
settle in West Germany, it was reported said Monday.
   The Daily Express newspaper said the six members of Komische
Oper, including singers and technicians, slipped away from a hotel
hours before the 320-member company was due to fly back to East
Berlin on Sunday.
   Officials at Covent Garden's Royal Opera House, the West German
Embassy and the British Home Office, which deals with asylum
requests, all said they knew nothing of the reported defections.
   East German Embassy spokesman Manfred Rudolph refused comment.
   The Daily Express said the six were staying at ``safe houses'' in
London.
   It quoted a lighting engineer, Fred Spodzieja, as saying he
wanted to get to the West ``to be free'' and to join his girlfriend
who fled to West Germany last year.
   ``There are so many reasons. But the main one is I want to be
free. I don't like the Berlin Wall. I want to be in the West,'' the
paper quoted Spodzieja, 41, as saying.
   The Komische Oper, on its first visit to London, was acclaimed by
critics and audiences and played to packed houses. Its performances
included ``Orpheus'' and ``Eurydice'' in modern dress.
   A West German embassy spokesman said the six had not contacted
the embassy.
   However, a BBC-TV report showed a man who it identified as
Spodzeija outside the embassy on Monday. He was shown smiling, but
said nothing.
   West Germany embassy spokesman Bruno Weber said was no need for
any East German defectors to contact the embassy because they had an
automatic right to settle in West Germany. They could simply fly to
West Germany from London.
   ``They basic law says Germans have to the right to travel freely
in Germany. They are our compatriots,'' said Weber.
</TEXT>
