<FIRST>r a AM-Pigeons-HomelessMan     08-14 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pigeons-Homeless Man,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Arrested for Killing Pigeons for Peanuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM FOREMAN Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man arrested at the Capitol for killing
seven pigeons if they beat him to a peanut thrown by tourists could
have gotten a meal, the executive director of one downtown soup
kitchen said Monday.
   ``What I couldn't understand was if this was going on on a
continuing basis, why didn't the people stop feeding the pigeons,''
said Margaret Dockery, executive director of the Shepherd's Table
soup kitchen, about two blocks from where the man was arrested.
``There are plenty of places around here to eat.''
   People feeding peanuts to pigeons Sunday evening near Capitol
Square told police a man was killing any bird that reached a nut
before he did. Police said if a pigeon beat the man to the nuts, he
would wring its neck.
   Police said they had no idea if the incidents on Sunday were the
first time such a thing had occurred.
   Eladio Castillo, 65, was cited for violating a city ordinance
that makes it illegal to ``trap, hunt or otherwise kill ...
starlings or similar birds or fowl'' in an area declared a bird
sanctuary by the city, Lt. R.C. Friese said.
   Castillo is scheduled for a Sept. 18 court appearance. The
citation carries an unspecified fine and court costs as penalty.
   Although there were two soup kitchens within blocks of Capitol
Square, including the Shepherd's Table, neither was open at the time
Castillo was cited. The Shepherd's Table closes on weekends and The
Salvation Army's kitchen opened at noon Sunday, but closed 30
minutes later, according to a spokeswoman for the Raleigh mission.
   Ms. Dockery said she wasn't familiar with Castillo, although she
said she might recognize him if he had been to her kitchen. She said
if the man had been in Raleigh for any time, he should have known
about the Shepherd's Table.
   ``It's very well known,'' she said. ``We have been down here for
nine years. There's a camaraderie among the folks. Even if they
don't know the precise hours, we have a sign in the window.''
   Ms. Dockery said she has encountered people in her kitchen who
have needed more than attention to their nutrition.
   ``What is the major gap is in the mental health problem,'' she
said. ``A lot of times, one will make the other worse. They will
come in here sometimes and it's very obvious that they haven't been
eating because their minds are not organized enough to take care of
themselves.''
   Ann Burke, director of Urban Ministries, said she is aware that
the hungry will go through trash bins in search of food, but she had
never heard of anyone fighting animals for food.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
