<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Vacancies     08-14 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Vacancies,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Smith Plane and AM-Ethiopia-Leland</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Vacancy List Grows to Five with Smith's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of Rep. Larkin Smith in a plane crash
within 24 hours of official confirmation of Rep. Mickey Leland's
death brought to five the number of vacancies in the 435-member
House of Representatives.
   Three seats had been left vacant earlier this year by the
resignations of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and House
Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., and the death of Rep. Claude
Pepper, D-Fla.
   Smith, R-Miss., perished in the crash of a single-engine plane in
Mississippi Sunday night. Several hours earlier, rescue teams
confirmed the crash of a twin-engine plane on an Ethiopian
mountainside. Leland was among 16 people killed in the African crash.
   No arrangements had been set Monday for special elections to fill
the seat held by Leland, D-Texas, and Smith, a former Mississippi
county sheriff.
   Their deaths left the party lineup of the House at 255 Democrats
and 175 Republicans.
   In a special Texas election last Saturday to choose a successor
to Wright, Democrat Pete Geren and Republican Bob Lanier finished
one-two. The pair will now compete in a runoff election to be
scheduled probably in September for the Fort Worth district seat
that the Democrats held for 34 years before Wright resigned amid
allegations of ethical misconduct.
   In California, Democratcic state Assemblyman Gary Condit is
trying to succeed Coelho, who resigned in mid-June as questions were
raised about his financial dealings. Over the weekend, the San
Joaquin Valley Republican Party endorsed Clare Berryhill, a one-time
high-ranking California agriculture official who has entered the
campaign for the Sept. 12 primary.
   In Florida, Cuban-born state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen won the
Republican nomination earlier this month to succeed Pepper. In the
Democratic race, attorney Gerald Richman had 28 percent of the vote
Aug. 1 while former Miami City Commissioner Rosario Kennedy, also a
native of Cuba, had 27 percent and Jo Ann Pepper, niece of the late
Florida Democrat, garnered 24 percent. A runoff will pit Richman
against Kennedy on Tuesday with the winner facing Ros-Lehtinen on in
a general election Aug. 29.
</TEXT>
