<FIRST>r a AM-RovingSands     08-14 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Roving Sands,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Multiforces Stage Largest Air Defense Exercise in Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT BLISS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-five soldiers parachuted into West
Texas early Monday, launching the first attack in the largest
air-defense artillery exercise ever conducted in the continental
United States.
   The mountains and desert of Texas and southern New Mexico are the
backdrop for the two-week, multiforce Exercise Roving Sands.
   Since the beginning of the month more than 8,000 soldiers, airmen
and Marines have been converging on Fort Bliss Army post along with
aircraft and artillery.
   The mock battles of the exercise will be carried out at Fort
Bliss, Biggs Army Airfield, White Sands Missile Range air space,
Holloman Air Force Base, N.M. and at Roswell, N.M.
   ``It's being done on this scale so that it can coordinate the
movements and activities for not only the Army but the Marines as
well and the capabilities of the Air Force,'' said Brad Rose, Fort
Bliss spokesman.
   Rose said similar scale practice maneuvers have been carried out
previously in Europe, but never in the United States.
   The 11th Air Defense Artillery Brigade, based at Fort Bliss, is
running the exercise.
   The operation has brought in Air Force units from Cannon,
Holloman and Kirtland Air Force Bases in New Mexico; Carswell AFB in
Fort Worth and Tinker AFB in Oklahoma. Also participating are
Marines from El Toro and Camp Pendleton and from Yuma, Ariz.
   ``The Marine Corps is playing the bad guys,'' said Sgt. First
Class James Swartz.
   The operation began at 6:30 a.m. Monday when the 65 soldiers
attacked the headquarters of the 11th Army brigade, Swartz said.
   Five AH-10 fighters have been flown in from Missouri and
Louisiana for the exercise. To transport equipment the troops will
use CH-54 ``Sky Crane'' helicopters from Birmingham, Ala.
</TEXT>
