<FIRST>r w AM-FarmLabor     08-14 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Labor,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Employment Up in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of workers employed by farmers
showed a seasonal increase in July but was down slightly from a year
ago, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   A quarterly report said the hired work force on farms was
estimated at 1,197,000 workers during the week of July 9-15, up from
830,000 in April. A year ago in July the work force was 1,200,000.
   Those did not include 351,000 ``agricultural service'' workers
provided by crew chiefs and labor contractors. In April, those
totaled 198,000 workers, and in July 1988 they were estimated at
303,000.
   Rain in the Delta states and much of the Southeast during the
survey week limited fieldwork in many areas, the report said.
   The report said the national figures for hired workers had a
sampling error of 7 percent.
   Average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was $5.23
per hour, up from $4.90 per hour a year earlier but below the
average of $5.35 in April, the report said.
   For workers hired by contractors, there was no national wage rate
available. However, workers in California were reported at $5.80 per
hour, compared with $6.45 in April and $5.74 a year earlier in July
1988. Florida workers averaged $5.55 per hour, compared with $6.24
in April and $5.19 a year earlier.
</TEXT>
