<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru 0635 08-14 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, 0635,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missile Tests Conducted Near Remote Hawaiian Islands Despite Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf and inserts 3 grafs before last graf pvs with
more on intended target area.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, despite two high-level U.S.
appeals, last week conducted an intercontinental missile test near
two remote Hawaiian Islands, Bush administration officials said
Monday.
   The 8,000-mile-range, unarmed missile, launched from the Soviet
Union, flew between the two tiny islands, Necker and Nihoa, shortly
before splashing down Friday 1,250 miles southeast of Oahu.
   The Soviets had announced Aug. 7 their intention to conduct a
test sometime between Aug. 11 and Aug. 21. Neither of the two
private U.S. appeals to Deputy Ambassador Serge Chetverikov nor the
test itself was made public.
   ``It's somewhat disturbing the Soviets didn't take our concerns
into account,'' a U.S. official said Monday. ``There was no danger,
but there is always a risk, however slight, it might be that
something would go awry. That is why we felt it was inappropriate.''
   Assistant Secretary of State Raymond R. Seitz and his deputy,
Curtis W. Kamman, met last Monday and Tuesday with Chetverikov to
complain that the missile was likely to pass over the Hawaiian
Island chain before splashing down, two U.S. officials said.
   Seitz and Kamman are the senior officers in the State
Department's Bureau of European and Canadian Affairs.
   ``The U.S. government expressed its deep concern to the Soviets
over the planned test and asked that it be modified,'' the U.S.
official said.
   Chetverikov returned to the State Department on Wednesday to say
the test would be conducted strictly over international water.
   ``We did not find that response persuasive or sufficient, because
the Soviet missile test would pass over the Hawaiian Island chain,''
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It is not
a legal issue but an issue of political and safety considerations.
Once again, we strongly urged the Soviets to reconsider their
plans.''
   In the U.S. appeals to the Soviets, the planned test was
described as a ``provocation,'' said another U.S. official, who also
requested anonymity.
   U.S. relations with the Soviet Union have been on the upswing in
most areas of the world, although there have been recent
disagreements over U.S. assistance to rebels in Afghanistan and
Soviet overtures to Iran.
   Despite the U.S. appeals, the Soviets tested the missile, which
splashed down shortly after passing over the 600-kilometer channel
between Necker and Nihoa.
   As it turned out, the missile did not pass over either island.
The point of the U.S. complaint, one official said, was that ``it
was too close for comfort.''
   The Soviets' initial notice had said the targeted spashdown area
was a circle, with a radius of 30 nautical miles, about 1,200 miles
south of Oahu.
   Actually, one official said, the missile touched down about 1,250
miles south of Oahu.
   In their notice, the Soviets said another missile test might be
conducted within the Aug. 11-21 period as well, with a spashdown
target of a rectangle about 1,200 miles northwest of the Hawaiian
islands. Evidently that test was never conducted, but the reasons
why could not be learned.
   Two years ago, in a similar situation, the Soviets revised a
missile test near the Hawaiian chain when the Reagan administration
objected.
</TEXT>
