<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Panama-Drugs     08-14 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Drugs,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanian Bank Laundered Drug Money, Fined $5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian bank pleaded guilty to
drug-laundering charges Monday and the United States, Canada and
Switzerland will share $5 million in seized drug trafficking profits
as a result, the Justice Department announced.
   ``This international cooperation in the war against drugs sends a
message to drug traffickers everywhere that it is going to be harder
for them to hide their ill-gotten profits, and easier for us to
recover them,'' Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said.
   The department said Banco de Occidente of Panama pleaded guilty
in U.S. District Court in Atlanta to aiding Colombia's Medellin
Carter in laundering cocaine proceeds via wire transfers from the
United States to Panama and then to Europe.
   Chief Judge William C. O'Kelley ordered the bank to forfeit $5
million in substitute assets to make up for drug profits that had
been transferred to other accounts.
   The department said U.S. agencies will split $3 million of the
money and $1 million each will go to Canada and Switzerland.
   Under legislation enacted in 1986, the United States can seize
property owned or under the control of narcotics traffickers even
when the actual drug profits are no longer available for seizure.
   ``Moving the assets of illegal drug trafficing out of one bank
account and into another can no longer cover up the illegal act,''
Thornburgh said. ``It is like fingerprints that cannot be brushed
away.''
   The Panamanian bank and the Banco de Occidente of Cali, Colombia,
were charged as an outgrowth of the ``Operation Polar Cap''
investigation of the laundering of illegal drug profits.
   Charges against the Colombian bank were dismissed as a result of
the Panamanian bank's guilty plea to a two-count indictment. The
department said the Colombian bank guaranteed to the United States
the full payment of the Panamanian bank's forfeiture.
   The government said its evidence showed that the drug proceeds
were effectively removed from the United States and then passed
through Banco de Occidente.
</TEXT>
