<FIRST>u i AM-Sweden-Wallenberg     08-14 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Wallenberg,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Invite Wallenberg Family for Talks on Missing Diplomat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has invited a
delegation of family and friends of Swedish diplomat Raoul
Wallenberg to Moscow to discuss his disappearance 44 years ago, an
official said Monday.
   Wallenberg, who would be 77, is credited with saving tens of
thousands of Hungarian Jews from Nazi concentration camps in World
War II.
   He was arrested by the Soviet army when it entered Budapest in
1945. Moscow has said he died of natural causes in prison in 1947,
but Soviet dissidents claimed to have seen him alive as late as 1986.
   The invitation to a four-member group indicated the Soviets might
release more information about Wallenberg's fate, said Sonja
Sonnenfeld, secretary of the Wallenberg Association.
   ``Just to repeat that old information would not be enough to
invite us,'' she said. ``The Soviets must be aware that there should
be new aspects.''
   It was the first time Soviet officials offered to meet
Wallenberg's family or association officials to discuss the case,
Ms. Sonnenfeld said.
   It was not immediately clear when the invitation was issued, but
Ms. Sonnenfeld said the group planned to travel to Moscow in
mid-October.
   Soviet officials invited Wallenberg's half-sister Nina Lagergren
and half-brother Guy von Dardel, Ms. Sonnenfeld and Per Anger,
Wallenberg's assistant at the Swedish Embassy in Budapest, she said.
   The group was promised meetings with high-level officials, Ms.
Sonnenfeeld said, ``but no names were mentioned and we didn't
insist.''
   Wallenberg issued Swedish travel documents to 20,000 Hungarian
Jews who were slated for Nazi concentration camps. His intervention
with German authorities was credited with the survival of another
100,000 Jews from the country's prewar community of 750,000.
   The Soviets never explained why Wallenberg was arrested. Some
historians believe he was mistaken for an American spy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
