<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0629,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Firebomb Israeli Tax Collectors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to include claim of responsibility; picks
up 3d pvs `Soldiers clamped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinians hurled
firebombs at a car carrying Israeli tax collectors Monday and
seriously burned two people in the car, the army said.
   Two men in the front seat suffered burns over 40 percent to 60
percent of their bodies, said Ruth Meckel, spokesman for Hadassah
Hospital in Jerusalem. A man and a woman in the back seat were
slightly injured.
   Israel radio said the radical Moslem group Islamic Jihad group
claimed responsibility for the attack, in a statement issued in
Amman, Jordan. The group has no known relation to kidnappers in
Lebanon who use the same name.
   Soldiers clamped a curfew on the area of Ramallah where the
attack occurred, and Israel radio said about 40 Palestinians were
detained.
   Soldiers also welded shut the doors of about 10 neighborhood
shops, a common punishment.
   There have been repeated confrontations between Israeli
authorities and Palestinians over non-payment of taxes. Underground
leaders of the anti-Israeli uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip have urged Palestians to withhold taxes to undercut
Israel's economy.
   In the past, the government has seized Palestinians' identity
papers to force payment of taxes.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, masked youths set ablaze a bus
carrying Arab workers to jobs in Israel. Arab reporters said no one
was injured because the youths ordered the driver and passengers off
the bus before setting it afire.
   Preventing Palestinians from working in Israel also is a tactic
of the uprising leaders.
   The Moslem fundamentalist movement Hamas, or Zeal, claimed
responsibility for the bus burning in slogans painted on walls in
black and green paint.
   At least 536 Palestinians have been killed in clashes with
soldiers or Israeli civilians since the uprising began in December
1987. Thirty-eight Israelis have been slain.
   Right-wing and Jewish settler leaders said Monday a leading
rabbi's declaration that Jewish law could permit trading occupied
land for peace is dangerous and may lead to ``the bloodshed of our
homeland.''
   The statement by Rabbi Ovadia Yosef on Sunday night drew the
strongest ire from the Gush Emunim settler movement, which believes
Jews must retain the West Bank and Gaza Strip for religious reasons.
   Israel seized the land from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle
East War.
   ``It's a shame that a great man of Israel did damage to the
nation of Israel, especially now when we need to be united,'' said
Gush Emunim spokesman Noam Arnon.
   Yosef, spiritual mentor of the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, is
considered one of the greatest experts on Halacha, or Jewish law.
   Right-wing legislator Geula Cohen, whose Tehiya Party advocates
annexing the West Bank and Gaza Strip, said Yosef was opening the
way for Israel's enemies to gain territory.
   ``He is calling on our enemies to threaten us with war,'' she
said. ``He is responsible for this, the bloodshed of our homeland,
not only our people.''
   Yosef told 1,000 Orthodox Jews that the government could return
occupied land if it saved Jewish lives and avoided war.
   Israeli newspapers Sunday reported that Yosef, a former chief
rabbi, has received death threats from extremists since his
statement.
   In Tunisia on Monday, U.S. Ambassador Robert H. Pelletreau Jr.
met for three hours with a Palestine Liberation Organization
delegation in the fourth formal session since the U.S.-PLO dialogue
opened last year.
   The dialogue began after the PLO renounced violence and
recognized Israel's right to exist.
   Pelletreau said the meeting in a suburb of Tunis was held at the
request of the United States. No details were released.
   The Palestinian delegation was led by Yasser Abd-Rabboo, a member
of the PLO executive committee, who said the discussions would
continue ``in the near future.''
</TEXT>
