abduction. Picks up 14th graf pvs, `The man...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDINER, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armed assailant beat and handcuffed a
man Monday and abducted his wife and two young children, who were
found later huddled next to their mother's body in a wooded area,
police said.
   A 21-year-old man was arrested on charges of murder and
kidnapping at about 5:45 p.m. after he turned himself in for
questioning at a police station about 110 miles north of Augusta,
state police spokesman Randy Nichols said.
   Byron Raines of Gardiner, who was employed by an electrical
contractor in the Augusta area, was being held in the Kennebec
County Jail while awaiting arraignment on Tuesday or Wednesday,
Nichols said.
   Authorities said family members identified the dead woman as Peg
Shaw, 35, who had been reported abducted early in the morning.
   By early afternoon, police had put out an all-points bulletin for
Raynes. Nichols refused to say whether there was any evidence
putting him at the scene in the Shaw home in this Augusta suburb.
   Nichols identified the father who was struck on the head as John
Shaw, and the children as his son, Sam, 3, and daughter, Julia, 1.
The children were reunited with their father, police said.
   ``They're somewhat in a state of shock, as can be expected,''
Nichols said. ``They have no apparent physical injuries.''
   About 6:30 a.m., an assailant entered the Shaw home, striking
Shaw in the head with a wooden mallet and then handcuffing him in
the basement, Nichols said.
   About an hour later, neighbors heard Shaw screaming for help.
Police were notified, and while they were questioning Shaw, the
family's silver Toyota van drove by the house, Nichols said.
   ``Mr. Shaw points it out. The police took chase,'' Nichols said.
``We feel at that point that the suspect was alone.'' He did not
elaborate on what the suspect might have done with the family at
that point.
   The van was soon discovered abandoned at some railroad tracks
near downtown Gardiner and the Kennebec River, Nichols said.
   Early in the afternoon, a state police trooper noticed some
tracks coming from a muddy road in South Gardiner. Nearby, the
trooper found the woman's body and the two children huddled together.
   The man was believed to be armed with a handgun.
   ``Mr. Shaw is OK,'' Nichols said. ``He's at a neighbor's house
being taken care of.''
   ``We have no information on a motive at this time,'' Nichols
said. ``It's being handled as an abduction, a kidnapping, and an
assault, obviously, and what has prompted it, we're unable to
determine at this time.''
   Police at the scene were using an airplane to search the area,
and several boats were being used on the Kennebec, Nichols said.
   By late morning, authorities had also set up roadblocks on U.S.
201 between Augusta and Gardiner and on U.S. 201 at the
Kennebec-Sagadahoc county line, Deputy Police Chief Craig Marshall
said.
