<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Poison     08-14 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Poison,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says Iran Made Two Attempts to Buy Hazardous Fungi in Netherlands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND de LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAARN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's attempt to buy poison-producing
fungi in the Netherlands in February was its second try in a year, a
spokesman for a Dutch research agency said Monday.
   An Iranian organization approached the Central Bureau for Fungus
Cultures last year about several types of fungus that can be used to
produce mycotoxin, a substance commonly called ``yellow rain,'' said
spokesman Huub van der Aa. Mycotoxins can be fatal in sufficient
quantities.
   The Iranian Research Organization for Science and Technology in
Tehran made similar request in February, Van der Aa said. On Sunday,
the New York Times reported that Iran also tried to acquire the
fungi in Canada.
   ``We refused to provide the fungi last year because the Iranians
were unable to clarify what they needed the stuff for,'' Van der Aa
told The Associated Press in a telephone interview from this Dutch
town 18 miles east of Amsterdam. He said he did not remember exactly
when the first request arrived.
   His agency, a branch of the Netherlands' Royal Academy of
Sciences, was advised by the Foreign Ministry this year of an
anticipated request and its possible purpose, Van der Aa said. The
academy is an independent institution partly financed with
government funds.
   A Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Monday: ``We heard reports ... in an informal
circuit of like-minded nations'' that regularly discuss the global
flow of fungi and bacteria for commercial and scientific purposes.
   She said the informal group was made up ``several nations within
the OECD area.'' The Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development has 24 members, including all NATO nations, Japan and
neutral countries such as Austria, Finland, and Switzerland.
</TEXT>
