<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-PlaneCrashes     08-14 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Plane Crashes,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Smith Plane and AM-Ethiopia-Leland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Seventeen Have Died in Air Crashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reps. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and Larkin Smith,
R-Miss., were the 16th and 17th members of Congress to be killed in
air crashes since 1928, according to the House historian.
   The remains of Leland's twin-engine plane were found Sunday in a
remote area of Ethiopia where it crashed while transporting the
congressman and 15 others to a refugee camp.
   Smith's private plane went down in a forest area in Mississippi
Sunday night, killing both the first-term congressman and his pilot.
   ``This is unprecedented outside of wartime in my experience to
lose two such promising members by accidental death in the same
week,'' Speaker Tom Foley said Monday.
   Another notable year was 1972 when three members of the House
were killed in crashes, two on the same aircraft.
   The plane carrying Reps. Hale Boggs, D-La. and Nick Begich,
D-Alaska, disappeared during a campaign trip in Alaska. The plane
was never found.
   Boggs' wife, Corrine C. ``Lindy'' Boggs ran for his seat and is
in her ninth term representing the New Orleans area.
   The same year, Rep. George Collins, D-Ill., died when the plane
he was riding crashed during a landing at Midway Airport in Chicago,
killing 44 other people as well.
   His wife, Cardiss Collins, was elected to fill his seat and is in
her ninth term in the House.
   Another congressional wife to win her husband's seat after a
plane crash was Katharine Edgar Byron. She was married to Rep.
William Byron, D-Md., who was killed in 1941 when his plane went
down at Jonesboro, Ga., near Atlanta.
   Her daughter-in-law, Rep. Beverly Byron, D-Md., now is in her
sixth term representing the same district, which she won after her
husband Rep. Goodloe Edgar Byron, elected to the seat in 1971, died
from a heart attack.
   Until this weekend, the most recent plane death among congressmen
was Rep. Larry McDonald, D-Ga., who was on KAL Flight 007 when it
was shot down by oviet fighter planes over the Sea of Japan in 1983.
   Two senators have been killed in plane crashes. Sen. Bronson
Cutting, R-N.M., died in 1935 in a crash near Atlanta, Mo., and Sen.
Ernest Lundeen, of the Farmer-Labor Party in Minnesota, was killed
in a plane that went down in 1940 near Lovettsville, Va.
   Other victims of aircraft accidents, according to historian
Raymond Smock and congressional staff:
   _Rep. Thaddeus Sweet, R-N.Y., 1928, in Whitney Point, Broome
County, N.Y.
   _Rep. William Kaynor, R-Mass., 1929, near Washington, D.C.
   _Rep. John Ditter, R-Pa., 1943, near Columbia, Pa.
   _Rep. Robert Coffey, D-Pa., 1949, in Albuquerque, N.M.
   _Rep. George Bates, R-Mass., 1949, at Washington National Airport.
   _Rep. Clement Miller, D-Calif., 1962, near Eureka, Calif.
   _Rep. Jerry Pettis, R-Calif., 1975, in a private plane in
Banning, Calif.,
   _Rep. Jerry Litton, D-Mo., 1976, in a private plane at
Chillicothe, Mo., Municipal Airport shortly after take-off.
</TEXT>
