<HEAD>Kidnappers Back In Brazil After Gunbattle In Paraguay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with kidnappers landing in Brazil,
stealing truck, surrounded by police; Pickup 11th pvs: The drama...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four armed kidnappers who freed three
hostages and escaped to Paraguay in a plane provided by authorities
flew back to Brazil Monday after a gunbattle with Paraguayan police,
officials reported Monday.
   They said the plane carrying the kidnappers, identified as two
married couples, landed on a farm in Toledo in southern Brazil and
the four stole a truck and drove south toward the Paraguayan border,
about 50 miles away.
   The fugitives, who last week obtained a $42,000 ransom in
exchange for a 9-year-old boy they had kidnapped, briefly took a
farmworker hostage after landing in Toledo but released him before
fleeing, local police spokesman Eduardo Silva said.
   He said police had spotted and surrounded the truck near the
Paraguayan border.
   Earlier, Brazilian police said they thought the plane had flown
north to Bolivia after the shootout with Paraguayan police..
   In Brasilia, the capital, federal police spokesman Paulo Marra
said the pilot and co-pilot of the twin-engine Cessna aircraft were
released when the plane landed in Toldeo and were questioned by
officials there.
   The two had volunteered to fly the fugitives from the town of
Presidente Prudente in southern Brazil to a destination of the
group's choice. They flew south to Paraguay, where the band's leader
reportedly owns a farm.
   But the plane was refused permission to land at a clandestine
airstrip near Hernandarias about 20 miles over the border. The four,
armed with hand grenades, submachine guns, pistols and shotguns,
exchanged gunfire with Paraguayan authorities, Marra said.
   ``The Paraguayan government did not authorize the plane to land
in its territory,'' Marra said. ``There was an exchange of gunfire,
and the co-pilot was shot in the right forearm.''
   In an interview with Globo television, the pilot, Aniceto de
Oliveira Gomes said, ``When we landed in Paraguay we were met by
gunfire. I thought I was seeing a film about Vietnam.''
   The Paraguayan Embassy in Brasilia confirmed the plane had landed
near Hernandarias and that it was surrounded by police but denied
there was a shootout.
   The drama that took police on a ten-day car chase through three
Brazilian states began Aug. 3 when 9-year-old Said Agel Filho was
abducted in front of his home in central Goiania, 135 miles
southwest of Brasilia, the capital.
   Six days later, police traced a phone call from the kidnappers to
the boy's family and surrounded a house on the city's outskirts. The
kidnappers negotiated the ransom and an armored car to escape.
   Three adults, including two television news reporters, then
offered to exchange places with the boy, and the kidnappers accepted.
   The group later released one of the reporters and headed for the
Goiania airport with the driver as the third hostage.
   But authorities there refused to give them a plane and pilot and
the kidnappers then set off on a 500-mile trip through the states of
Goias, Minas Gerais and Sao Paulo.
   The hostages were released unharmed Sunday after authorities in
Presidente Prudente provided the kidnappers with a plane and the
pilot, Oliveira Gomes, a rancher and a local mayor. The co-pilot was
identified as Antonio Seregatti.
   Brazilian police lost track of the plane soon ater it took off
late Sunday afternoon because it was flying at an extremely low
altitude.
</TEXT>
