<HEAD>News Anchor Threatened, Man Charged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infatuated fan who wrote letters and sent
gifts to a news anchorwoman for five years was arrested for
allegedly threatening to shoot the KNBC-TV newswoman, authorities
said Monday.
   Warren Sevy Hudson, who allegedly told a co-worker he was ``bored
with life and that he was going to Burbank to shoot Kelly Lange,''
was charged with making a terrorist threat on the TV anchorwoman.
   The district attorney's office said that for five years Hudson,
57, had been writing letters, making phone calls and sending gifts
to Miss Lange, which were returned.
   An executive at KNBC contacted the district attorney's office
last Thursday and said he had been notified of the threat, which
allegedly was made last Wednesday, authorities said.
   Police launched an investigation, interviewed the co-worker and
found out that Hudson had been fired Thursday from his job as a
laborer at a gold bullion exchange.
   Hudson was arrested Friday at a motel where he lived. Police said
they recovered a .38-caliber Colt revolver and ammunition when they
arrested him.
   Hudson was scheduled to be arraigned Tuesday, and the district
attorney's office said they would ask for $50,000 bail.
   Ms. Lange and KNBC-TV had no comment on the arrest, said station
spokesperson Regina Miyamoto. ``This is in the hands of the police,
the district attorney and the courts,'' Ms. Miyamoto said.
   A recent spate of threats and acts of violence against
celebrities have produced concern and even legislation on the issue
of celebrity safety.
   Robert John Bardo, 19, described as an ``obsessed fan'' of
actress Rebecca Schaeffer, is charged with shooting her to death at
the door to her Los Angeles apartment on July 18.
   In response to Schaeffer's slaying, state assemblyman Mike Roos
announced Aug. 1 he planned to introduce legislation to restrict
public access to address information held by the Department of Motor
Vehicles.
   In June, a state parole board delayed for at least nine months
the release on parole of Arthur Jackson, convicted of a nearly fatal
knife attack on actress Theresa Saldana in 1982. From prison,
Jackson wrote letters threatening Ms. Saldana.
   Jackson's eligibility for parole after serving seven years of a
12-year prison sentence has been assailed by Ms. Saldana. It
inspired a new state law to keep violent, mentally ill prisoners in
mental hospitals after they complete their sentences.
   Last December, two guards were shot and killed at Universal
Studios last December by a man who demanded to see actor Michael
Landon, star of ``Highway to Heaven.''
