<FIRST>r a AM-LAPhilharmonic     08-14 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Philharmonic,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finnish Conductor Esa-Pekka Salonen Chosen to Lead LA Philharmonic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finnish conductor Esa-Pekka Salonen said
Monday he has agreed to succeed Andre Previn as music director of
the Los Angeles Philharmonic.
   The 31-year-old Salonen's appointment was formally announced at a
Music Center news conference.
   ``This is one of the happiest days of my life with the
Philharmonic,'' said Michael J. Connell, president of the
Philharmonic Association's Board of Directors.
   Managing Director Ernest Fleischmann said the appointment is
``sending a signal to the world that we mean business'' about the
orchestra's future.
   Salonen will be the 11th conductor in the orchestra's 70-year
history. He accepted the position, he said, because ``it's a great
orchestra and the artistic potential involved is enormous.''
   He said he felt he already had developed good rapport with its
musicians.
   Salonen has served as principal conductor of the Swedish Radio
Symphony and principal guest conductor of the London Philharmonia
since 1985. He also is principal guest conductor of the Oslo
Philharmonic.
   He will retain his post with the Swedish Radio Symphony when he
assumes his new position in Los Angeles. Under the contract, Salonen
will assume the directorship at the beginning of the 1992-93 season
and will continue through the 1994-95 season.
   Salonen won international attention in 1983 when, with less than
a week's notice, he conducted the London Philharmonic in a
performance of Gustav Mahler's Third Symphony.
   He made his U.S. debut the following year with the Los Angeles
Philharmonic and went on to lead the orchestras of West Berlin, New
York, Chicago, Boston, Philadelphia, Paris, Montreal, Minneapolis
and Washington.
   Also a composer, Salonen is known as a champion of contemporary
work and a supporter of avant-garde experimentation.
   ``My experience is you have to combine things, showing that
contemporary music is the result of the traditional, the older
music,'' Salonen said. ``If you make the right, interesting
combination, it works.''
</TEXT>
