<DOCNO> AP890814-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Europe-Collider     08-14 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Collider,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giant European Atom Smasher Produces Z Particles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists at Europe's new particle accelerator,
the world's biggest, said Monday they have produced the first
specimens of a kind of particle from which they expect to gain clues
to the basic forces of nature.
   The successful start of the atom smasher, the Large
Electron-Positron Collider, paves the way for ensuring `'Europe's
position at the forefront of particle physics research throughout
the next decade,'' the European Laboratory for Particle Physics said
in a statement.
   Scientists shooting beams of particles _ electrons and positrons
_ around the 17-mile circular tunnel under the Swiss-French border
reporded the LEP produced its first so-called Z particle Sunday,
said the lab, known by its former French acronym CERN.
   A month after its first test run, LEP's giant detectors, more
than 5,000 magnets and other parts have proven to be ``working and
ready to produce results,'' CERN said.
   By the fall, LEP is expected to produce thousands of Zs daily,
creating a greater scope for detailed study than its innovative but
less prolific U.S. competitor, the Stanford Linear Accelerator at
Menlo Park, Calif., according to the statement.
   LEP, built over eight years with 1.3 billion Swiss francs ($790
million) from CERN's 14 members states, is the most powerful
particle accelerator and the largest scientific instrument ever
made, according to CERN.
   It said the machine will recreate with new sophistication the
dense swirl of matter just after the Big Bang, the explosion
scientists believe created the universe 15 billion years ago.
   Z particles existed naturally only for an instant after the Big
Bang. By watching them decay into other particles, CERN scientists
hope to get new insight into the structure of matter and the
development of the universe.
   In particular, results of the Z experiments are expected to help
complete a scientific model explaining the interaction of nature's
postulated four basic forces _ gravity, electromagnetism and the
weak and strong forces.
   Carlo Rubbia, the Italian physics professor who heads CERN,
shared the 1984 Physics Nobel Prize with Dutch scientist Simon van
der Meer for discovering the Z at CERN. But stronger colliders were
needed to make enough so scientists can draw well-founded
conclusions from the random ways the particle breaks down.
   One of the most fascinating results may be the discovery of an as
yet theoretical particle believed to be the key to mass _ why things
weight what they do.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890814-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 2104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Leland-US 1stLd-Writethru a0690 08-14 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leland Mourned on Capitol Hill; Condolences Pour In</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Smith-Plane Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Leland, 44, to CORRECT number of trips to
Ethiopia; picks up 6th graf, It was</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The question rang out Monday at a Capitol
memorial service for Rep. Mickey Leland and three congressional
staffers who died with him: ``We ask God, `Why These?' They're our
best.''
   Across Capitol Hill, staff members from other representatives'
offices were pitching in, answering phones and doing other chores as
condolences poured into Leland's House office.
   Elsewhere, hunger organizations were coming forward with ideas
for memorializing the Texas Democrat's work.
   While workers were struggling to recover the bodies of Leland and
15 others who died when their plane crashed in a rugged area of
Ethiopia, the shock of Sunday's announcement that they had indeed
been killed was giving way back home to a resigned sadness and
promises to follow his lead.
   Leland, 44, chairman of the House Select Committee on Hunger, was
on his sixth visit to Africa and his second this year when his plane
crashed Aug. 7 en route to Fugnido refugee camp. The wreckage was
discovered Sunday.
   It was his second trip to the region since March to focus
attention on the need for hunger relief for hundreds of thousands of
Sudanese, who have been forced from their homes by the country's
long-running civil war.
   At the Capitol service, in the stately caucus room of the Russell
Senate Office Building, Senate aide Robert Mallett said, ``This
mission was a mission of mercy. It was the best our country had to
offer. It showed our compassion, our generosity, our interest in
seeing that there are no more hungry people, the children would not
die of hunger.''
   ``We ask God, `Why These?' said Mallett, an aide to Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas. ``I suppose the answer lies somewhere in thinking
about the condition of the world. They went about doing good. To
heal the world.''
   Mallett said, ``We're going to see that there are no more hungry
children in Ethiopia, anywhere in the world. In that way, we will
know that in your dying, you have challenged us to live.''
   On the crimson-carpeted platform behind him, four white candles
flickered in silver candlesticks. Velvet drapes covered the arched
windows, as mourners wiped away tears or hid their crying eyes in
their hands.
   ``We gather today with heavy hearts as we join with his staff,
his family, and Senate staff in this great, immeasurable loss,''
prayed Senate Chaplain Richard C. Halverson. ``We remember the
hungry and the homeless for whom he laid down his life.''
   The memorial service, sponsored by the Senate Black Legislative
Staff Caucus, honored congressional members of the entourage in
addition to Leland: Patrice Y. Johnson, Leland's chief of staff;
Joyce Williams, a staff member with Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., and
Hugh A. Johnson Jr., a staff member of the Hunger Committee.
   Elsewhere at the Capitol, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley said,
``There will be a determination on the part of members of the House
to work for those goals that Mickey Leland sought to achieve, the
alleviation of hunger and suffering here and in Africa and elsewhere
in the world.''
   Foley said Leland's willingness to return to Africa time after
time, despite unstable political conditions and the risks of travel,
was a ``testament to his determination individually to follow
through on commitments and values that were very, very close to him.
   ``And I think other members will also be willing to assume those
risks and I don't think this will change,'' said Foley.
   Letters, telegrams and phone calls of condolence continued to
pour into Leland's office Monday, as staff members from other
congressional offices pitched in to help.
   Staff members from at least 10 members' offices had been helping
out through the weeklong vigil for word of Leland's whereabouts, and
after the sad news arrived early Sunday morning.
   Clara Pinzana, who is press secretary to Rep. Greg Laughlin,
D-Texas, said of Leland's own staff, ``They're doing really well.
They have burned the candle at both ends, but you wouldn't know it.''
   In Dallas, meanwhile, about 500 mourners gathered at the Peoples
Missionary Baptist Church for a memorial service sponsored by the
Interdenominational Ministers Alliance of Dallas.
   The Rev. S.M. Wright, president of the alliance, said Leland had
worked closely with many political and religious leaders in Dallas,
trying to solve statewide problems.
   ``He was like family to our elected officials here,'' Wright said.
   Meanwhile, hunger organizations that worked with Leland were
beginning to come forward with ideas for memorializing his work.
   One of them, Rev. Larry Jones, whose Feed the Children ministry
takes in about $40 million a year for international hunger projects,
said a feeding center in Ethiopia will be named for the congressman.
   ``I don't want what he stood for to die,'' said Jones, whose
non-profit organization is based in Oklahoma.
   An aide in the White House foreign press office said Monday that
a congressional and White House delegation that would be sent
accompany the remains of Leland and other Americans back to the
United States was ``currently on hold.''
   The bodies have to be recovered and identified, the aide said,
before a decision can be made on when the delegation would leave.
Four congressmen and two White House officials have been asked to
accompany the remains on their return home.
</TEXT>
