<FIRST>r a AM-ChemicalDerailment     08-14 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Derailment,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brakeman on Derailed CSX Train Used Cocaine, Federal Agency Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brakeman on a chemical train that
derailed last month, forcing 3,000 people to flee, used cocaine
sometime in the 48 hours before the accident, a federal agency said
Monday.
   Blood and urine samples provided by the brakeman, who wasn't
identified, tested positive for cocaine, the Federal Railroad
Administration said in a news release. Samples provided by the
engineer and conductor tested negative.
   Railroad administration spokeswoman Claire H. Austin in
Washington, D.C., said the brakeman, whose name was withheld, was
riding on the lead locomotive of the 37-car CSX Transportation Co.
train when 14 cars derailed July 22.
   A fire that began in some of the derailed cars caused the
evacuation of about 3,000 people. Twelve people were injured.
   ``His role in the cause of the accident, if any, has yet to be
determined,'' Austin said.
   Two days after the accident, CSX spokesman R. Lindsay Leckie
announced that the brakeman admitted himself to a drug and alcohol
rehabilitation center.
   The federal agency also announced Monday that it will conduct a
safety audit of CSX's line between Midland and Toledo, Ohio. The
audit, which includes inspections and checks of maintenance
procedures, began Monday. A report is due Sept. 1.
   The National Transportation Safety Board discovered worn wheels
and brakes on the derailed train and found a variety of operating
violations.
</TEXT>
