<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 2138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica     08-14 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azcona Says Democratic Opening Exists In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo said
Monday that moves toward democracy by Nicaragua's Sandinista
government allowed him to vote for disbanding that country's
U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   The Honduras-based guerrillas, ``should understand that the
military option against Nicaragua was canceled in the Tela
meetings,'' Azcona said in reference to the Central American summit
in the Honduran port city last week.
   An accord, which was put together by Honduras and approved by the
five Central American presidents, calls for the rebels to be
repatriated in 120 days.
   Azcona's position is central to the accord's success because
Honduras has allowed the so-called Contras to operate from its
territory. If Honduras abides by the accords, the rebels will find
it difficult to survive.
   An agreement between the Nicaraguan government and its political
opponents shortly before the Tela summit ``weighed heavily in the
decision to approve the plan demobilizing the rebels,'' Azcona said.
``Nicaragua, undoubtedly, is experiencing a democratic opening.''
   Under the agreement, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega promised
fair elections in February and to end the draft. Ortega has also
granted an amnesty to all Nicaraguan rebels living in Honduras and
Nicaragua.
   The United States, which since last year has given only
humanitarian aid to the Contras, has said it will abide by the Tela
accord.
   But in Miami, a Contra leader reiterated that the rebels will not
lay down their weapons. Rebel leader Enrique Bermudez called for
Nicaraguan citizens to provide the rebels with aid.
   ``We call on peasants and workers in ... Nicaragua to support the
freedom fighters with food and clothes to maintain the struggle
against the Sandinista regime.''
   The peace accord calls for the United Nations and Organization of
American States to set up a verification commission within 30 days
to plan and monitor repatriation of the 11,000 Contras and 12,000
dependents living in Honduras. The Contras have fought the
Nicaraguan government since 1981, saying the Sandinistas betrayed
the ideals of the revolution that overthrew Anastasio Somoza in July
1979.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras agreed March 21 to suspend
offensive operations, but talks aimed at a permanent end to the
7-year-old war in which 50,000 people have died stand at an impasse.
</TEXT>
