<SECOND>AM-Doctor Killer,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Gets Maximum for Murder, Rape of Doctor From India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of raping and murdering a young
doctor from India was sentenced to the maximum prison term of 33 1-3
years to life on Monday.
   Dennis Scotto, 40, was convicted June 30 of second-degree murder
and rape in state Supreme Court in Brooklyn. In September 1987, he
entered the Brooklyn apartment of Sunita Movva, 24, sexually
attacked her, beat her with his fists and then stabbed her
repeatedly, according to trial testimony.
   Scotto ``caused unspeakable grief to the victim's family and
friends, who loved her dearly. This defendant deserved the maximum
sentence allowed, and I'm glad that is what he got,'' Brooklyn
District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman said after State Supreme Court
Justice Philip Lagana delivered the sentence.
   Scotto lived in an upstairs apartment with his mother. He had a
history of mental illness and had been arrested on nine previous
occasions, including five times for burglary.
   Ms. Movva and her husband, Sadasiva Katta, also a doctor, moved
from India to Chicago in 1986. They had lived in Brooklyn less than
a month when Ms. Movva was murdered. After the killing Katta moved
to Detroit.
   ``Whatever sentence is imposed ... she will not be returned to
me,'' Katta said in a letter read before the sentencing. ``But
please do not belittle the loss or devalue the worth of Sunita's
life, a young physician who could have served humanity.''
