<FIRST>u a AM-Smith-Plane 3rdLd-Writethru a0683 08-14 0999</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smith-Plane, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0683,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Larkin Smith Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 22nd graf: ``Four other,'' with two grafs bgng: ``Six other,''
to CORRECT that six, not four, congressmen have been killed in post-1972
plane crashes (</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX17, HAT1, JX1 and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW AUGUSTA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Larkin Smith, a former
sheriff known for his strong law-and-order stance, was found dead
Monday with his pilot in the wreckage of a small plane that crashed
in a forest.
   The freshman Republican, whose plane disappeared Sunday evening
during a 90-mile flight from Hattiesburg to Gulfport, became the
second congressmen in as many weeks to die in an air accident.
   Rescuers spotted the wreckage of the single-engine Cessna 177
from the air about 8 a.m. Monday. Searchers had to bulldoze their
way to the wreckage in the thickly wooded DeSoto National Forest 14
miles south of here, authorities said.
   ``The plane was all to pieces,'' said Perry County Deputy Sheriff
Gene McRee. ``It appeared it centered a big pine tree. There was no
way anyone could have survived.''
   The plane's engine appeared to have been dead when it crashed,
said Dr. Michael West, deputy medical examiner for neighboring
Forrest County. West said there was no sign of fire or smell of
gasoline at the crash site.
   Smith, 45, was elected to Congress last November from the 5th
District, taking the seat of fellow Republican Trent Lott, who ran
successfully for the U.S. Senate. Before his election, Smith was
sheriff of Harrison County and, before that, police chief of
Gulfport.
   Gov. Ray Mabus ordered state flags to be flown at half-staff,
saying Smith ``had dedicated his life to public service.'' Smith's
seat will be filled by special election.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater read this
statement:
   ``President and Mrs. Bush deeply regret the news of the death of
Congressman Larkin Smith. The president knew and supported
Congressman Smith during his election to a seat vacated by Sen.
Trent Lott. Congressman Smith was just beginning a promising career
in the Congress.''
   Earlier Sunday, word had come from Ethiopia that the wreckage of
a plane carrying Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and 15 other people
had been found with no survivors. The plane disappeared Aug. 7 on a
flight to a remote village. Searchers on Monday began efforts to
recover the bodies.
   Smith and his pilot, Chuck Vierling, left Hattiesburg shortly
after 9 p.m. Sunday after Smith had thrown out the first baseball at
the Dixie Youth World Series. John Walker, a spokesman for the
congressman, said the plane went off radar at 9:25 p.m.
   Skies were reported clear in the area Sunday night, but former
Hattiesburg Mayor Bobby Chain said he flew in just before the crash
and there was a thick haze at 5,000 feet, making it ``easy for a
pilot to lose his horizons.''
   Dozens of military, civilian and law enforcement rescuers
searched for the plane after a resident reported that he thought he
heard a plane crash.
   ``My wife was preparing to go to bed, and we heard a plane coming
over,'' said the man, Lamar Breland. ``I thought at the time it was
unusal for a plane to be in the area at night.'' Breland said he
heard a ``revving sound, and then a crash.''
   The wreckage was first spotted Monday morning by a U.S. Customs
Service aircraft. The bodies were thrown from the wreckage, which
was shattered except for part of the tail section, authorities said.
   A Federal Aviation Administration investigator was on the scene.
   In his seven months in Congress, Smith had co-sponsored
legislation to strengthen federal drug law enforcement, and
criticized federal drug czar William Bennett for backing a ban on
semi-automatic assault weapons from other countries.
   He once took fellow Judiciary Committee members to an FBI
shooting range to demonstrate his belief that shotguns were just as
dangerous as assault weapons. He claimed 90 percent of crimes were
committed with pistols and shotguns.
   He advocated making death penalty laws uniform across the
country, eliminating paroles and early release for dangerous
criminals, and streamlining the federal appeals process, which he
called ``never-ending.''
   ``He was so happy and enjoying being a member of Congress,'' said
Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., who had joined Smith at
opening ceremonies at youth baseball series. ``He was doing a super
job as a member. He had emerged as one of the real leaders in the
freshman class of the 101st Congress.
   ``Our last conversation at the series was talking about the loss
of Congressman Leland, and I told Larkin that he should be careful
in traveling and performing his duties.''
   Six other congressmen have died in plane crashes since 1972.
Majority Leader Hale Boggs, D-Louisiana, and Rep. Nick Begich,
D-Alaska, died when their plane disappeared over Alaska in Oct. 16,
1972. Rep. George W. Collins, D-Illinois, was one of 45 people who
died Dec. 8, 1972, in the crash of a United Airlines jet in Chicago.
   Rep. Jerry Pettis, R-Calif., died in a private plane crash in
Banning, Calif. Rep. Jerry Litton, D-Mo., was killed Aug. 3, 1976 in
a private plane at Chillicothe, Mo., Municipal Airport shortly after
take-off. And on Sept. 1, 1983, Rep. Larry McDonald, D-Georgia, was
one of 269 people who died when the Soviets shot down a Korean
Airlines jet in Soviet airspace.
   In addition to the Judiciary committee, Smith was a member of the
House Government Operations committee and on task forces
concentrating on defense, crime and the savings and loan industry.
   He began his career in law enforcement in 1966. In 1977, he was
appointed police chief in Gulfport.
   Then in 1983, running as a reform candidate, he defeated
incumbent Leroy Hobbs to take over the scandal-ridden Harrison
County Sheriff's Department. Hobbs eventually was convicted of
racketeering and drug charges.
   Smith is survived by his wife, Sheila; a daughter; and a grandson.
   Funeral arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
