<DOCNO> AP890814-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 2224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Irish 4thLd-Writethru a0719 08-14 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0719,0880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode, Sporadic Violence on Troops Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with two bombs exploding; Pickup
4th pvs: In this...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs, one in
Londonderry and the other in Belfast, exploded late Monday amid
scattered rioting marking 20 years since British troops arrived in
Northern Ireland.
   Police issued a statement saying the Londonderry bomb was thrown
at an armored police Land Rover and the blast rocked the vehicle and
broke windows in nearby homes but injured no one.
   The Belfast bomb, also apparently aimed at security forces,
exploded in the Roman Catholic Ardoyne district, according to
police. They gave no details.
   In sporadic rioting, IRA supporters threw rocks and gasoline
bombs at police, who responded with plastic bullets. Police said two
demonstrators were injured but that their conditions were not
serious.
   Earlier, marchers paraded through downtown Londonderry chanting
``IRA! IRA!'' as they passed police patrols and the ruins of a bar
destroyed two days earlier by an Irish Republican Army bomb.
   During the day in Belfast, police fired plastic bullets to
disperse youths who set fire to at least four vehicles in scattered
violence. Police said there were no injuries.
   In this northern city where ``the troubles'' began, several
thousand people joined the march from Creggan, a Catholic district,
down through the Bogside, the Catholic area where fighting with
police prompted the dispatch of British troops on Aug. 14, 1969.
   Marchers went down the hill to the ``Free Derry'' corner at the
edge of the Bogside, with its sign saying ``You Are Now Entering
Free Derry.''
   The pub was left in ruins by a bomb that exploded four hours
before the huge annual Protestant march Saturday commemorating the
end of the Catholic siege of Derry 300 years ago. No one was injured.
   Central Londonderry was sealed off Monday after police noticed
two suspicious beer barrels, but reopened after midday when it was
concluded to be a hoax.
   Armored military Land Rovers blocked streets that were closed to
the march.
   The rally after the parade illustrated divisions within Northern
Ireland's Catholic minority. Only one speaker mentioned the Rev. Ian
Paisley, the Protestant militant, but four denounced John Hume,
leader of the largest Catholic political party.
   ``We've all risked our lives for 20 years, and I say fight on!''
said Martin McGuinness, vice president of Sinn Fein, the legal
political wing of the outlawed IRA.
   Bernadette Devlin McAliskey, a protest leader in the 1960s and
70s, urged continued organizing toward unification of Ireland as a
``32-county workers' republic.''
   She said she wanted democracy, equality and the right to say what
she thought without fear, and ``nobody can give them to me as a
present in a wee box. ... John Hume can't negotiate them.''
   It was a quiet and orderly crowd of 5,000 to 6,000. After the
speeches there was a large bonfire of scrap wood, discarded
furniture and tires.
   Opponents of the marchers within the Catholic community stayed
home.
   The division among Irish nationalists has been as persistent and
difficult to heal as the Protestant-Catholic split at the root of
the years of violence.
   Both the Social Democratic and Labor Party and Sinn Fein advocate
a united Ireland, but Sinn Fein backs the IRA's violent campaign
against British rule of the province. The SDLP advocates peaceful
change, saying more innocent civilians have been killed by the IRA
than by security forces.
   Londonderry was a focus of Catholic civil rights marches a
generation ago. Protestants were a majority in the province, but a
minority in Londonderry and resorted to gerrymandering and job and
housing discrimination there to keep control.
   It is revered by Protestants as the town where their ancestors
withstood a Catholic-led siege in 1689. Their annual commemorative
parade sparked the violence in 1969.
   ``History shows that oppression gives rise to resistance. The
only way to end the violence is to end the injustice,'' McGuinness
wrote in a 20th anniversary edition of the Derry Journal newspaper.
   ``The use of armed struggle for the IRA, supported by a large
section of the nationalist community, is as natural as the use of
violence by the defenders of the Bogside 20 years ago.''
   Hume, the Catholic political leader, said the IRA has caused many
of the province's troubles.
   ``We have emergency legislation. We have troops on our streets.
We have young people being continually stopped and searched. We have
house searches. We have checkpoints. We have prisons full of young
people,'' he wrote in the Derry Journal.
   ``Every man and woman in the street knows one simple way to end
those problems. If the IRA ended their physical force campaign
tomorrow and devoted themselves to peaceful means alone, then in a
matter of weeks the troops would be gone from streets.''
   Hume has defeated McGuinness twice in parliamentary elections. In
1987, the vote was 23,743 to 8,707.
   More than 2,740 people, two-thirds of them civilians, have been
killed in Northern Ireland since 1969 and dozens have died in
attacks in Britain, the Irish Republic and continental Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
