<HEAD>Boy Critically Shoots Friend While Playing `Robocop'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Names in 2nd graf are cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WORTH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old boy who found a handgun in
the trunk of his uncle's car wounded a 5-year-old playmate Monday
while the boys were imitating the movie ``Robocop,'' police said.
   Ronelis Frendeles was in guarded condition at Bethesda Memorial
Hospital with gunshot wounds to both legs, said police spokeswoman
Lori Nedzweckas.
   The 7-year-old child told officers he found his uncle's
.38-caliber handgun and it went off while the boys were imitating
``Robocop,'' a violent movie about a half-man, half-robot
``supercop.''
   The shooting remained under investigation, police said.
   A recently passed state law, which takes effect Oct. 1, is
designed to deter just such a shooting in the wake of the
liberalization of Florida's gun laws.
   Under the new law, adults can be charged with a felony,
punishable by up to five years in prison and a $5,000 fine, if a
child shoots himself or another because of the owner's carelessness.
