<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-BoatPeople     08-14 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Boat People,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Boat People Arrive in Southern Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wooden boat carrying 137 Vietnamese refugees
arrived in southern Japan early Monday and officials said they would
be transferred to Japan's only refugee reception center, which is
already overcrowded.
   The 66-foot boat with 112 men and 25 women aboard was discovered
near the Goto Islands 610 miles southwest of Tokyo, said Masataka
Sasahara, a spokesman for the Maritime Safety Agency.
   No injuries or sickness were reported among the group and
Sasahara said the boat people were resting in a tent set up by a
local village office.
   He said the Vietnamese told officials they had left the northern
port of Haiphong on June 25 but he had no further details.
   Sasahara said the boat people would be moved to Nagasaki for
health examinations and an immigration inspection before being
transferred to the nearby Omura Temporary Refugee Reception Center.
The reception center is overcrowded with 415 refugees waiting to be
granted permanent residence in Japan or to be accepted by other
countries, the agency spokesman said.
   Hisao Nishino, deputy director at the center, said the facility
has a capacity of 200 people and ``it is impossible to receive any
more.''
   The increase in the number of Indochinese refugees this year has
raised concern and some government officials have said Japan will
have to provide more facilities to house and process them.
   Refugee officials said 1,262 Indochinese arrived this year
compared to only 187 in 1988.
   ``It's just too much, and the government should do something
about it right now,'' Nishino said.
</TEXT>
