<FIRST>r a AM-DrugAgentSlain     08-14 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brother-In-Law of Former Mexican President Held in Camarena Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in-law of former Mexican President
Luis Echeverria was flown here from Texas on Monday and ordered held
without bail as a material witness in the 1985 torture-slaying of a
U.S. drug agent.
   Several informants have named Ruben Zuno-Arce as a major drug
trafficker in Guadalajara, Mexico, and have indicated he talked
about U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena's murder, said a government
affidavit filed with the arrest warrant for Zuno-Arce.
   Zuno-Arce's attorney and friend, Jeremiah Handy of San Antonio,
said his client is a successful Mexican businessman who deals in
lumber and vegetables, and has no history of drug trafficking.
   Zuno-Arce, a resident of Mascota, Mexico, was arrested Wednesday
in San Antonio by U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service agents.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie, who issued the arrest
warrant last week, said he would hold a bail hearing next Monday and
ordered Zuno-Arce held without bond until then.
   Handy said not setting bail on a prisoner who has not been
charged was unusual, but ``this is an unusual case.''
   The kidnapping and torture-slaying of Camarena and his pilot,
Alfredo Zavala-Avelar, turned into an international incident. The
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration has vowed to pursue every
person involved in the killings.
   Several members of the Mexican federal police force were linked
to the slayings. One, Raul Lopez Alvarez, was convicted in Los
Angeles last year with two drug traffickers.
   Earlier Monday, a police officer from the western Mexican state
of Jalisco was arraigned in Los Angeles on an indictment charging
him with kidnapping, murder, racketeering and being an accessory
after the fact.
   The officer, Juan Jose Bernabe Ramirez, pleaded innocent to the
charges, and his trial was tentatively set for Oct. 3.
   Bernabe was arrested July 27 as he was about to return to Mexico.
According to a DEA affidavit filed at the time of his arrest,
Bernabe told two undercover DEA agents he was present when reputed
Mexican drug lord Rafael Caro-Quintero tortured Camarena.
   Camarena and Zavala-Avelar were killed after the agent led a
series of damaging raids on marijuana plantations allegedly operated
by Caro-Quintero, authorities have said.
   Camarena's body was found on a ranch 65 miles southeast of
Guadalajara, the capital of Jalisco.
   Seven more men are charged with murder and conspiracy in the
case, including Caro-Quintero, who is in custody awaiting trial in
Mexico City.
   Camarena and Zavela-Avelar are believed to have been killed at
Caro-Quintero's Guadalajara home. The arrest warrant for Zuno-Arce
identifies him as the former owner of the home.
   Handy, however, said his client does not know Caro-Quintero
``except as a name in the paper like anyone else.''
   Zuno-Arce has been subpoenaed to testify before a federal grand
jury in Los Angeles on Aug. 23, and the government is seeking his
testimony at Bernabe's trial.
   The affidavit signed by DEA Special Agent Abel Reynoso said
investigators believe Zuno-Arce is a major drug trafficker in the
Guadalajara area.
   The affidavit said it was suspected Zuno-Arce may have been a
witness to ``events surrounding the kidnapping and murder of special
agent Camarena.''
   Zuno-Arce is the brother of Echeverria's wife. Members of his
family attended Monday's court session. Echeverria was president of
Mexico from 1970 to 1976.
</TEXT>
