<FIRST>r a AM-McCoySentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0614 08-14 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCoy Sentencing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0614,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCoy Sentenced For Robbery, Killing, Counterfeiting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT sentence to 43 years, sted 48 years;
UPDATE with second sentencing, sentencing of Moore, comment by judge denying
appeal bond, victim's sister; CORRECT that McCoy and girlfriend, sted Moore
and girlfriend, were convicted.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of West Virginia's
biggest bank robbery and in jail-escape and murder-for-hire plots
was sentenced Monday to life in prison plus 43 years.
   John P. McCoy, 43, of Slater's Branch, Ky., also was fined
$250,000 by U.S. District Judge Charles Haden II and ordered to make
restitution if proceeds from the bank robbery are found.
   McCoy also was sentenced by U.S. District Judge Robert Staker to
nine years and fined $12,500 on counterfeiting and conspiracy
convictions. The prison sentences are to be served concurrently.
   An accomplice, David Doyle Moore, 39, of Forest Hill, Ky., was
convicted in the holdup. Harden sentenced Moore to 29 years and
three months in prison, the maximum for robbery, conspiracy and
intimidating a witness.
   McCoy, who stood trial three times this summer, was convicted of
robbing the Matewan National Bank branch in Kermit of $286,000 in
January 1987, killing an accomplice, threatening and intimidating
federal witnesses, counterfeiting $800,000 in U.S. currency,
plotting a jail escape and hiring a contract killer.
   Despite being convicted on all but one count, McCoy said he
believed each of his convictions would be overturned on appeal.
   ``I feel very comfortable that it (the truth) will come to show
itself,'' McCoy said last week in an interview in federal prison in
Ashland, Ky.
   Haden sentenced McCoy to more time than was recommended under
uniform sentencing guidelines established in 1987.
   ``The court feels the guidelines really did not contemplate this
much criminal conduct out of one person,'' said Haden, who rejected
Moore's request that he be released on bond pending his appeal.
   McCoy claimed prosecutors and Haden were angry because he fought
them through legal services work he began after serving two years in
prison for mail fraud in the early 1980s.
   ``They've taken thieves, chauvinists and prosecutors to come
after me. The honorable Judge Haden has not afforded me the first
iota of justice,'' McCoy said.
   McCoy was convicted in June of the bank robbery, the subsequent
murder of accomplice Russell Davis, two conspiracy counts and the
threatening of federal witnesses.
   Davis' sister, Angie Dobson, traveled from her home in Pensacola,
Fla., to witness the sentencing.
   ``It was worth it,'' she said. ``I think he's been proven
guilty.''
   In July, McCoy and his girlfriend, Debbie Farley, 36, of Fort Gay
were convicted of counterfeiting conspiracy. McCoy also was
convicted of counterfeiting. They used a color photocopying maching
to make what federal agents said were relatively poor copies of U.S.
and Canadian currency.
   Two weeks ago, McCoy and three others, including his 21-year-old
son, Kennis, were convicted of hiring a man to kill witnesses and
family members. No one was killed or injured. McCoy also was
convicted of concocting a jail-escape plot that failed.
</TEXT>
