<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1400EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   08-14 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Whisper to a Scream'' (Virgin Vision. VHS-Beta, $79.95. Rated R)
   
   ``Whisper to a Scream'' is an ordinary movie about serial
murders. In this case, the victims are nightclub dancers who get
sliced and diced by the sleazy joint's weirdo disc jockey.
   It's a an amateurish production at best, and one wonders why such
a distinguished actor as Yaphet Kotto would want to be in it. He
plays the police detective assigned to solve the murders.
   The dancers are supposedly artist types but they do tend to take
off their clothes a lot. In addition there are sexual situations,
strong language and, of course violence as the women are strangled
and stabbed.
   Nadia Capone plays a struggling young actress who gives up a
promising part to stay with her painter-lover (Silvio Oliviero). To
make ends meet she works in a backroom of the nightclub talking
suggestively to guys who apparently like to pay for obscene
telephone calls, including the weirdo deejay, who likes to record
the sounds of the dying females for his ultimate muscial
composition. He thinks of Capone as his muse.
   As he begins to stalk her as his final victim, she suspects her
lover of rubbing out her co-workers.
   All in all, the movie looks like it was slapped together by a
group of unemployed actors and actresses who decided to make a movie
over the weekend with rented equipment in someone's loft.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Land Before Time'' (MCA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $24.95. Rated G)
   
   ``The Land Before Time'' is one of the few animated children's
features of recent years that can hold a candle to the old Walt
Disney classics. No surprise that it's primarily the creation of Don
Bluth, who worked for Disney before he left to start his own company.
   The film tells the simple story of Littlefoot, a lovable baby
brontosaurus, who must make his way from his homeland, which is
being wracked by earthquakes and volcanoes, to a green oasis known
as the Great Valley.
   Along the way, Littlefoot is separated from his grandparents,
sees his mother killed, fights off the villainous Sharptooth and
makes friends with other young creatures of varying shapes and
species.
   Bluth and his co-producers, John Pomeroy and Gary Goldman, manage
to make these primordial characters appealing without being
sickeningly cute. The animation is inventive and the dramatic scenes
_ like the big earthquake or Sharptooth's attack _ extremely vivid.
   Very young children may be frightened by these parts and upset by
the mother's death. But aside from that caution, this is that rare
film that can honestly be recommended for viewers of all ages. It
even holds up under repeated watching.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
