<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1401EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   08-14 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Grove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``In Step'' (Columbia) _ Stevie Ray Vaughan and Double Trouble
   
   The first solo on ``In Step'' is taken by pianist Reese Wynans.
That's a surprise, but it underscores the fact that Stevie Ray
Vaughan's blues guitar is not the record's sole raison d'etre
(French for ``reason to be purchased'').
   Vaughan's guitar is a remarkably expressive instrument, true. But
``In Step'' offers even more.
   Wynans, drummer Chris Layton and bassist Tommy Shannon play with
the same fire as the star. Horns on two cuts add further punch.
   The tunes are nicely varied, from boogie-woogie (``The House Is
Rockin''') to shuffle (``Tightrope'') to slow 12-bar blues (Buddy
Guy's ``Leave my Girl Alone''). Two instrumentals also alter the
pace. And the sassy-sounding ``Scratch 'n' Sniff,'' with Vaughan
showing he can sing as fast as he plays, justifies the inclusion of
a lyrics sheet.
   Vaughan belongs on any list of the best popular, contemporary
bluesmen. His music is as gritty as George Thorogood's, yet as
graceful as Robert Cray's. And what a guitarist!
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Quintets for oboe and strings by Arnold Bax and Arthur Bliss;
Phantasy Quartet for oboe, violin, viola and cello, Op. 2, by
Benjamin Britten; Pamela Woods, oboe and the Audubon Quartet (Telarc)
   
   Telarc dipped into the Cleveland Orchestra for Pamela Woods,
assistant principal there and a journeywoman oboist who has played
with the Cincinnati, San Antonio and Baltimore orcehstras, for this
satisfying program of English oboe music.
   Add her fat tone, seamless lines and fine musicianship to the
superlative Audubon, and the result is an excellent disc. Woods'
rich, round sound, unburdened by a heavy vibrato, blends perfectly
with the quartet. All are equals. If any fault can be found, it is
that Ms. Woods is sometimes on the nonchalant side when the music
needs a little more heat.
   The program is coherent. The pieces were composed between 1922
and 1932, all inspired by the great English oboist Leon Goossens.
The Bax-Bliss-Britten order moves from less tonal complexity to
more. The pieces, most in the Bax and least in the Britten, have
elements of British folk tunes, and all revel in a richness of
texture.
   Bax, also a poet who published under the name Dermot O'Byrne, was
enamored of Ireland and travelled widely there. The quintet's folk
melodies, most apparent in the last movement, bear out that bit of
biography. The piece has a lush quality and reminds one of the Ravel
string quartet. Doris Lederer's viola solos are particularly
beautiful.
   Bliss, a World War I veteran, succeeded Bax as Master of the
Queen's Music, and his quintet sounds inspired by the Bax work. His
variety of colors is greater, and Britten's even greater still.
Britten was 18 when he finished his Phantasy; it is one of his
earliest mature works.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
