<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Modine Adv25-27   08-14 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Modine, Adv 25-27,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 25-27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-WKD--Memphis Belle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Matthew Modine: A Good Film Role Is Hard To Find</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BINBROOK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matthew Modine has been widely acclaimed
as one of America's best young film actors, but the star of
``Married to the Mob,'' ``Birdy'' and now ``Memphis Belle'' says
good screen roles are hard to find.
   ``It's just so hard to find something you want to work on,'' he
said over lunch during a break in filming ``Memphis Belle.''
   ``When there's something good around, everyone knows about it.''
   The 30-year-old actor increasingly has been getting a sizable
share of what's good. Though the California-born Modine has appeared
in flops such as ``Vision Quest'' and ``Mrs. Soffel,'' he's best
known for starring in two attention-grabbing films about the Vietnam
War: Alan Parker's ``Birdy'' and Stanley Kubrick's ``Full Metal
Jacket.''
   Movies, he said, have a responsibility to their audiences, so he
is selective.
   ``Maybe, if I were in straitened circumstances, I wouldn't be
able to choose,'' he said. ``But fortunately, I can afford not to
work. ... There's so much garbage you read that is repetitious.''
   Modine said he was drawn to ``Memphis Belle'' by its tale of 10
ordinary men who are transformed into heroes. ``Memphis Belle''
relates 24 hours before the celebrated bomber's final mission, a
successful raid over Bremen in northwest Germany. The aircraft was
then brought back to the United States, where the same 10-member
crew flew it across the country as a propaganda exercise. In May
1987, it was restored and is now on display in Memphis.
   ``The propaganda machine said these guys did it so they must be
extraordinary human beings,'' he said. ``In fact, they weren't. They
were just the ones who did it.''
   He said the film was a ```Das Boot' in the air,'' referring to
the 1981 German movie about a World War II U-boat mission.
   Next up, Modine will be seen as a medical student who falls in
love with his teacher, played by Christine Lahti, in Thom
Eberhardt's ``Gross Anatomy.'' Beyond that, he is interested in
making a film that links AIDS to a conspiracy by the World Health
Organization.
   ``There's enough proof that the WHO asked for it,'' he said,
adding that the film, as yet untitled and unwritten, would be
similar in tone to the 1979 hit movie about a nuclear accident,
``The China Syndrome.''
   ``It's quite frightening. If it (the disease) was commissioned,
if this is what happened with AIDS, then the ramifications are
huge,'' Modine said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 25-27</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
