<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed today in early European
trading. Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar was supported by a wave
of buying enthusiasm and short-covering unleashed Friday by
diminished prospects that the U.S. Federal Reserve will ease
interest rates.
   Profit-taking by banks was working against the dollar, other
dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.83 yen to a closing 141.93 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 141.70 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.9378 West German marks, down from 1.9390;
1.6755 Swiss francs, up from 1.6705; 6.5480 French francs, up from
6.5455; 2.1848 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1685; 1,393.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,388.00; and 1.1745 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1754.
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.5882 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5850 late Friday.
   Gold was steady in quiet trading and bullion dealers said the
market was watching the dollar for clues to the metal's near-term
direction.
   Gold opened in London at $362.55 a troy ounce, compared with
late Friday's $362. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $363.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $362.90, up from $361 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 7 cents to close at $364.30.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.17 a troy ounce, up from
Friday's $5.10.
</TEXT>
