<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose today against the Japanese yen
for the third consecutive trading day while prices on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange declined.
   The dollar closed at 141.93 yen, up 1.83 yen from last Friday's
close of 140.10 yen. It opened at 141.85 yen and ranged between
141.48 yen and 141.95 yen. The dollar now has climbed 3.08 yen in
three trading days.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which fell 6.84 points in
trading Friday, declined another 41.34 points, or 0.12 percent,
closing at 34,671.62 points.
   The U.S. currency's gain in Tokyo today followed its rise in New
York last Friday, when newly announced producer price and retail
price figures indicated stability in the American economy, analysts
said.
   But Yasuo Miyakawa, an analyst for Sumitomo Bank, said Tokyo's
exchange market was relatively quiet Monday.
   ``Dealers are waiting for the announcements of the U.S. trade
statistics and the consumer price index later this week,'' he said.
   The stock market was quiet too.
   ``With the beginning of the summer vacation, there is nothing
new today,'' said a trader with Yamaichi Securities, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The Nikkei average lost 85.61 points in the morning but
recovered somewhat in the afternoon.
   The trader said Sony shares were bought, but no other single
issue attracted particular attention.
   A relatively light total of 380 million shares traded hands.
</TEXT>
