<FIRST>r f PM-Obit-Bardahl     08-14 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Bardahl,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Founder of Bardahl Oil Products Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ole Bardahl, the founder of a worldwide
manufacturing company whose name appeared on motor oil additives,
hydroplanes, race cars and racing airplanes, died Friday of
emphysema. He was 87.
   Bardahl, who died at Ballard Community Hospital which he helped
establish, was born in Trondheim, Norway. He immigrated to the
United States in 1922, arriving in Seattle with $32 to his name.
   In 1939, Bardahl bought a small soap and cleansers manufacturing
company that became Bardahl Manufacturing Corp. and eventually had
operations in 70 countries.
   But it was motor sports that gave him much of his fame.
   He introduced his first Miss Bardahl hydroplane in 1957, and
went on to win six national hydroplane championships, five Gold
Cups and two world championships. He also sponsored race cars for
21 years in the Indianapolis 500 and a championship P-51 airplane
named Miss Bardahl.
   Besides his wife, Inga, Bardahl is survived by two daughters,
seven grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
