<HEAD>Elders IXL Directors Formally Reject Harlin Holdings Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of Elders IXL Ltd. on Monday rejected
an offer by Harlin Holdings Pty. Ltd. that values the Australian
conglomerate at $4.1 billion.
   Harlin, a closely-held concern controlled by Elders executives
including company chairman John Elliott, has offered to buy Elders
for 3 Australian dollars a share, or a total of about 5.4 billion
Australian dollars.
   Elders' board, as expected, told shareholders Monday Harlin's
offer did not reflect the full value of the company.
   The directors cited a report by Elders' advisers, the investment
firm First Boston Australia Ltd., that valued the company's shares
at between 3.36 Australian dollars and 3.79 Australian dollars.
   Harlin already owns about 18 percent of Elders. Its offer for
all of the company is aimed at appeasing critics who say
shareholders are entitled to the same price that Harlin plans to
pay for an additional 17 percent jointly owned by AFP Group PLC and
Goodman Fielder Wattie Ltd.
   A number of international companies have agreed to supply Harlin
with funds to help it finance the offer for Elders.
   The companies, which agreed to buy new shares in Harlin, thereby
taking an indirect stake in Elders, are: Molson Cos., Prudential
Bache Interfunding Inc., Compagnie Financiere de Suez, Hong Kong &amp;
Shanghai Banking Corp., and Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Harlin also has arranged debt funding for its offer.
   Elders' businesses include brewing, agriculture, financial
services and resources.
</TEXT>
