<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-McDonnellDouglasFine     08-14 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McDonnell Douglas Fine,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Pays $180,000 Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has received
$180,000 from McDonnell Douglas Corp. as a civil penalty for
failing to maintain its approved quality control program for MD-80
jetliners, the FAA's Northwest Mountain Region office said.
   On Feb. 24, 1988, the FAA cited McDonnell Douglas for allegedly
violating federal aviation regulations by failing to incorporate a
mandatory design change in the manufacture of 171 of its
twin-engine MD-80s. Payment of the fine was announced on Friday.
   The design change required the Long Beach, Calif., plane builder
to harden areas around the attachment holes of a ``doubler'' or
reinforcing part for the planes' upper anti-collision light to
prevent fatigue cracking. The doubler strengthens the structure
around the light and attaches the light housing to the airplane.
   The hardening process, called stess coining, increases
resistance to fatigue cracking, guarding against possible
strucutral failure and depressurization in flight, the FAA said.
   The FAA found fatigue cracking in doublers of earlier DC-9
airplanes and issued an airworthiness directive on Dec. 17, 1985,
for all DC-9s in service. The directive ordered either stress
coining of the doubler or repeated inspections for cracking after
planes had 30,000 flights.
   At the same time, the FAA approved the design change to modify
the doubler on all MD-80 airplanes in production. The MD-80 is
McDonell Douglas's designation for later-model DC-9s.
   Since 120 MD-80s were produced and delivered without the
required design change, the FAA has since revised the airworthiness
directive to include those planes for repeated inspections or the
doubler modification.
   Another 51 aircraft were produced without the modified doubler
but the deficiency was discovered and corrected before they were
delivered to customers.
   The FAA originally proposed a $200,000 fine for McDonnell
Douglas but FAA spokesman David Duff said that was reduced after
the manufacturer showed it had complied with some provisions of the
design change. Duff said the fine was received by the FAA on Aug. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
