<FIRST>u f PM-CommoditiesProbe     08-14 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yen Pit Trader Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Chicago Mercantile Exchange yen pit trader pleaded innocent
today to charges stemming from the FBI's
probe of suspected fraud in the world's largest futures markets.
   Michael Sidel, 42, of Lake Forest, entered the plea before U.S. District
Judge George M. Marovich. He is the 13th yen trader to
plead innocent.
   Forty-six traders from the Merc and from the Chicago Board of Trade
were indicted Aug. 2 on charges ranging from pre-arranged
trading to racketeering, conspiracy and tax fraud.
   The indictments stem from a 2{-year undercover FBI investigation into
trading practices at the two exchanges. The probe is
continuing and more indictments are expected this fall.
   Sidel, accused of defrauding his customers, is charged with one count
of violating the Commodities Exchange Act and one count of
mail fraud.
   Sidel and the other 12 former yen traders all deny charges they took
part in alleged schemes to pocket profits from trades made
for customers while passing on their own trading losses to customers.
   Five people have pleaded guilty so far in the investigation.
   Anthony Onesto, Sidel's attorney, said he expects former yen pit trader
Thomas Braniff to testify against his client. Braniff,
33, pleaded guilty last week to two counts of violating the exchange act
and two counts of mail fraud.
</TEXT>
