<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PolaroidSuit     08-14 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid Suit,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Chairman Says He Thought Company Would Win Polaroid Patent
Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. Chairman Colby Chandler testified today he knew that
getting involved in instant photography
could mean a lawsuit from competitor Polaroid Corp., but he said he was
convinced his company would win.
   Chandler testified in a U.S. District Court trial that will determin
how much Kodak owes Polaroid for infringing on patents for
instant-developing film.
   Asked if he had felt there was a chance Kodak's introduction of an
instant camera in the mid-1970s could provoke a suit from
Polaroid, Chandler answered, ``Yes.''
   But he said, ``I felt we had reduced the risk to such a low level it
was not a major consideration.''
   An earlier federal court decision already established that Kodak infringed
on the patents of Polaroid, the Massachusetts-based
pioneer of instant photography.
   Polaroid is seeking $12 billion, which would be a record award in a
patent infringement suit, while Rochester, N.Y.-based Kodak
has argued it should pay $177 million, an amount equal to a royalty of
5 percent on the cameras and film it sold from 1976 to 1985.
   Chandler testified before Judge A. David Mazzone that Kodak's corporate
policies clearly state, ``We will not knowingly violate
or infringe'' another company's patents.
   Asked if he had any reason to believe that policy was violated when
Kodak entered the instant film business, Chandler said, ``No,
I did not.''
   Chandler said he relied on advice from the company's attorneys in deciding
that Kodak's product would not infringe on Polaroid's
patents.
   Asked if he had any reason to believe at the time the advice was faulty,
Chandler testified, ``No, I did not.''
   In May, Polaroid Chairman William J. McClune Jr testfied that Polaroid
and Eastman Kodak had a productive working relationship
for decades, with Kodak making film for Polaroid, but that things soured
in the late 1960s when Polaroid introduced its SX-70 camera.
   Kodak, McClune said, was asked to produce the new, complex negative
that Polaroid had developed for that instant color camera.
But he said Kodak demanded a license from Polaroid, which would have allowed
Kodak to develop its own instant photography.
   Polaroid ultimately built its own film manufacturing facilities in
Massachusetts.
   McCune testified then that instant photography is Polaroid's ``bread
and butter'' and that Kodak's introduction of instant film
and cameras cut deeply into his company's profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890814-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bush-SEC 2ndLd-Writethru   08-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-SEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Aide Picked to Head Regulatory Agency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf, White House, with Fitzwater comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has chosen Richard C. Breeden, the White House point
man on landmark savings-and-loan
legislation, to head the Securities and Exchange Commission, administration
sources said today.
   The formal nomination was expected later in the day, said the sources,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. The post requires
Senate confirmation.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater all but confirmed Breeden's
selection. ``Let's say that Mr. Breeden is an
outstanding candidate and I don't know that we have an announcement on
it today, but we expect to soon,'' Fitzwater said.
   Breeden, 39, a lawyer and banking specialist, would succeed David S.
Ruder, who announced in May that he intended to step down.
   Breeden helped write President Bush's plan for bailing out the nation's
ailing savings and loan industry, and represented the
White House in dealings with Congress as that legislation progressed through
Congress.
   The final plan, a major restructuring of federal banking laws and the
largest single-industry government bailout in history, took
effect with Bush's signature last week.
   Breeden, whose current job as presidential assistant for issues analysis
made him something of a White House troubleshooter, also
helped fashion administration policy for dealing with the Alaska oil spill.
   From 1982-85 Breeden was deputy counsel to then-Vice President Bush.
He came to the White House after four years in private
practice as a banking specialist in the Washington office of a Houston
law firm.
   The SEC is a five-member board that oversees securities markets, regulates
the sale of stocks, bonds and stock options and
enforces securities laws.
   Ruder, an appointee of former President Reagan, has been chairman of
the regulatory body since Aug. 7, 1987, some 2{ months
before the stock market crash.
   He announced last May that he wanted to step down, and would stay on
until a successor was selected. Ruder plans to return to
Northwestern University Law School, where he formerly taught.
   Breeden's nomination was not expected to run into any difficulties
in the Senate, which where he is reportedly well respected.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
