<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Darman-Fed 1stLd-Writethru   08-14 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Darman-Fed, 1st Ld-Writethru,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Backtracks on Criticism of Fed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Fitzwater comment; picks up pvs 4th graf,
Fed spokesman; adds byline. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House today backed away from a
contention by President Bush's budget director that the Federal
Reserve Board is inviting a recession by keeping interest rates too
high.
   ``Our policy is to want continued economic growth with low
inflation,'' said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater. ``We
believe the economy is generally on that course at the present time
and the Fed is doing a good job.''
   ``The Fed is aware of our policy objectives and we believe that
they share our concern for continuing economic growth,'' Fitzwater
added.
   Richard G. Darman, the director of the Office of Management and
Budget, sounded an alarm on central bank policy Sunday.
   ``I'm fearful that (Fed policymakers) have been a little bit too
concerned that things have been going well, and that they may have
been a bit too tight'' on interest rates, Darman said on NBC's
``Meet the Press.''
   ``If we do have a recession, it will be because they have erred
on the side of caution,'' said Darman. ``... I think it's quite
important that the Fed appreciate that growth is indeed fundamental
to the health of this economy, and that they not become too obsessed
with concern about things going well for too long.''
   Darman's television interview prompted a humorous exchange
between himself and Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter today at a
bill-signing ceremony at the White House.
   ``You were kind of ornery yesterday,'' a smiling Yeutter called
across the room to Darman. ``What do you mean?'' Darman replied.
``Work on it a little bit more, Dick,'' Yeutter said. ``I want to
refinance my home.''
   Fitzwater was careful not to criticize Darman.
   ``Dick is the director of the Office of Management and Budget,''
the spokesman said. ``He is a part of the economic team. We share
his thinking. He shares our thinking. But we think generally we're
on the right course here.''
   Fed spokesman Joseph Coyne said the agency would have no comment
on Darman's assertions.
   The U.S. economy has posted a record peacetime expansion since
emerging from the 1980-81 recession. The Fed began pushing interest
rates up in March 1988 when it began sensing that inflationary
pressures were building.
   However, the central bank changed course last June after
detecting weakness in the economy and has made three modest moves
since then to lower interest rates.
   But Darman called the moves insufficient, saying: ``I would say,
insofar as we are concerned about recession, we should all worry a
little bit about the Fed.''
   ``I think that there's no reason for us to have a recession,'' he
said. ``It's not necessary, if there is sensible management on the
parts of ourselves and the Fed.''
   Darman said he has shared his views with Greenspan and indicated
he did not see the perceived problem as the Fed chairman's alone.
   ``... I think we're (the Bush administration) under sensible
management, and it's important not merely that Chairman Greenspan
but the other members of the board and the (policy-setting Federal
Open Market Committee) that makes the crucial decisions on this ...
be more attentive to the need to avoid tipping this economy into a
recession,'' he said.
</TEXT>
