<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Fees     08-14 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Fees,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers in Eastern Case File For $7.4 Million in Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the lawyers involved in Eastern Airlines'
5-month-old bankruptcy case have filed applications for fees for
their work, amounting to a total of $7.4 million.
   Law firms representing Eastern, a committee of its major
creditors and a court-appointed bankruptcy examiner filed the
applications during the past week or so, a clerk in the U.S.
Bankruptcy Court said.
   Altogether, at least 135 lawyers have worked on the case since
Miami-based Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on
March 9, five days after the start of a crippling strike. Eastern
has filed a reorganization plan to rebuild to an airline two-thirds
of its pre-strike size.
   ``Bankruptcy is a trough and all of the animals in the barnyard
come to feed in it,'' Bruce Simon, the lead attorney in the case for
the Air Line Pilots Association, said Monday. ``Especially in a
bankruptcy context, the fees that are paid typically are
outrageous.''
   The $7.4 million in fees, which must be paid out of Eastern's
assets, covers the first four months of the proceeding. The
applications must be approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R.
Lifland, who has scheduled a court hearing on the matter for Sept.
5. Legal fees generally are approved in bankruptcy cases.
   The attorneys representing Eastern's three striking unions _ the
pilots, Machinists and flight attendants _ are paid by the unions
and aren't required to disclose their fees to the court.
   Simon, a partner in the New York firm Cohen, Weiss &amp; Simon, said
he would ``happily accept'' only 25 percent of his adversaries' fees.
   Harvey Miller, the lead lawyer for Eastern who often has dueled
with Simon in court, put in 804 hours of work on the case at the
rate of $375 an hour, for a total of $301,650. His associate, Bruce
Zirinsky, is asking for $300 an hour for 1,156 hours of work, or
$346,890.
   Miller and Zirinsky are with Weil, Gotshal &amp; Manges, a New York
firm specializing in bankruptcy law which has 80 to 85 attorneys
working on the Eastern case, for fees ranging from $70 an hour to
Miller's $375. The firm's combined fee application of $3.8 million
was the largest chunk of the total filed.
   ``These are our standard billing rates,'' Miller said.
   Attorney David Boies of Cravath, Swaine &amp; Moore, who is advising
Eastern and its parent Texas Air Corp., filed an application for
$298,000 on behalf of his firm. Lawyers for Eastern at other firms
are seeking a total of around $1.8 million.
   David I. Shapiro, the special examiner appointed by Lifland,
applied for $236,100 for 787 hours of work at $300 an hour. Fourteen
other attorneys in Shapiro's firm, Dickstein, Shapiro &amp; Morin of
Washington, D.C., asked for a total of $507,698 for 3,469 hours of
work on Eastern.
   Joel Zweibel, the principal attorney for the creditors'
committee, is seeking $241,500 for 644 hours at $375 an hour. His
firm, Kramer, Levin, Nessen, Kamin &amp; Frankel of New York, applied
for a total of $946,106 for 36 lawyers and 13 legal assistants.
   The firms will be required to file new applications every three
months until the airline emerges from bankruptcy, a goal Eastern
hopes to achieve by the end of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
