<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     08-14 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0376</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were lower in moderate afternoon
trading today in what continued to be a choppy session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 7.02 points to
2,676.97 at 3 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 7.78 points
at 2 p.m.
   Declining issues outpaced advances by about 2 to 1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 970 issues up, 472 down and 506 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 116.47 million shares.
   The market opened lower on profit-taking and behind a weak bond
market, then drifted up and down during the session.
   Blue-chip stocks rallied early in the afternoon but the broader
market failed to follow and the rally was soon aborted, analysts
said.
   In mid-afternoon, the bond market took a dive and stocks followed.
   ``I think this is another one of those bond squalls,'' said Gene
Jay Seagle, vice president of Gruntal Financial Inc., as stock
prices slipped by a falling bond market in the afternoon.
   On Friday, the bond market rose sharply in the morning after a
report that the producer price index declined 0.4 percent in July.
Bonds later lost more than a point after news that retail sales had
risen 0.9 percent, raising doubts that the Federal Reserve would
relax its credit policy further in the near future.
   This morning's report that business inventories rose 0.4 percent
in June was within expectations and had little impact on the stock
and bond markets.
   Analysts said the market could pick up more momentum later in the
week when the government reports on housing starts, merchandise
trade and consumer prices.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.84 to 191.43.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
1.26 to 379.38.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Hewlett Packard was
down 3[ at 52[, Paramount Communications was off 1[ to 60[ and
General Electric had lost ~ to 56}.
   IBM, meanwhile, was up [ to 115|, Eastman Kodak was up { to 50{
and Exxon had gained | to 44\.
