<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Drop on Forecasts of More Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed lower Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade as traders reacted to forecasts of rain
in crop-producing areas.
   Soybean prices were down sharply, after rising last week on an
Agriculture Department report projecting lower-than-expected soybean
production.
   ``All of the speculators who bought Friday were seen selling
aggressively on Monday,'' said William Biedermann, an analyst with
Allendale Inc. in Chicago. ``Rain in the forecast was the main
reason.''
   Forecasts on Friday called for dry conditions. But Monday's
forecasts called for rain in eastern crop areas early in this week,
and rain in western areas later in the week.
   ``Rain in August assures soybean producers a good crop,''
Biedermann said.
   Another factor on the soybean market is the South American
soybean crop, he said.
   Exports from South America are meeting international demand
before the U.S. harvest. Without sales from Brazil and Argentina,
the market would be tight, Biedermann said.
   Weekend rains and forecasts for more precipitation also put a
damper on corn and wheat prices.
   However, wheat futures rallied towards the close of trading, as
traders factored in Taiwan's bid for 300,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 3\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.95\ a bushel; corn was 3\
cents to 5{ cents lower with September at $2.28{ a bushel; oats were
5{ cents to 6 cents lower with September at $1.36 a bushel; soybeans
were 5 cents to 22} cents lower with August at $5.99 a bushel.
</TEXT>
