<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, Gold closed ..., with one graf to CORRECT
closing gold price. Deletes reference to afternoon price. An AMs version
planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed in quiet European trading
Monday. Gold prices rose slightly.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was positioning itself
before Tuesday's Assumption Day religious holiday, which will close
many European markets.
   Traders said confidence in the dollar remains high over the
medium term but few are willing to open big positions while the
currency ranges just below its recent highs.
   Should more traders change their minds about the dollar in the
holiday-thinned markets Tuesday, ``that could lead to some pretty
big jumps,'' said a London trader for a U.S. bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.83 yen to a closing 141.93 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 141.70 yen.
   Other dollar rates at Monday's close compared with late Friday:
1.9395 West German marks, up from 1.9390; 1.6760 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6705; 6.5535 French francs, up from 6.5455; 2.1832 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1685; 1,393.75 Italian lire, up from 1,388.00;
and 1.1775 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1754.
   In London, the dollar gained slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.5840 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5850 late Friday.
   Gold was steady in quiet trading, with bullion dealers watching
the dollar for clues to gold's near-term direction.
   Gold closed in London at a bid price of $364 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's 362.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.50, up from $361.00 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 7 cents to close at a bid
$364.30 an ounce.
   Silver rose in London to $5.21 a troy ounce from Friday's 5.10.
</TEXT>
