<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-14 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0238</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined in relatively slow trading
today, as the market paused after last week's frantic activity.
   The market opened lower on profit-taking and behind a weak bond
market, crept up slowly by late morning then began a seesaw action
that lasted through the entire trading session.
   A government report that business inventories rose 0.4 percent in
June had little impact on the market. Analysts said the number was
within market expectations.
   Blue-chip stocks rallied early in the afternoon but the broader
market failed to follow and the rally was soon aborted, analysts
said.
   Analysts said the market was due for a correction after last
week's hectic pace.
   ``It's normal to expect some profit-taking in the short term,''
said Ralph J. Acampora, technical analyst with Kidder Peabody &amp; Co.
``This could last several days. Once it's over we can expect people
to start buying again.''
   After peaking during Friday's session above the all-time high of
2,722.42 reached on Aug. 25, 1987, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
ended the session with its sharpest loss since late June, dropping
28.64 to 2,683.99. The market had tested the all-time high on
Thursday, closing at 2,712.63.
   Analysts said the market could pick up more momentum later in the
week when the government reports on housing starts, merchandise
trade and consumer prices.
</TEXT>
