<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel-States Bjt   08-14 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-States, Bjt,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel Expects to Pay $11.5 Million To Settle With States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has agreed to pay
$975,000 in fines to 10 states in an effort to clear its name and
operate freely around the country despite a guilty plea to federal
securities crimes, officials said Monday.
   Drexel said it expects to pay $11.5 million overall to settle
with the states, avoid litigation and retain its ability to do
business, but some states still want to revoke the New York
investment firm's brokerage license, according to securities
regulators.
   The settlements follow months of negotiations between Drexel and
a three- member panel formed by the North American Securities
Administrators Association that yielded an unprecedented pact
governing state operations of a Wall Street firm.
   Drexel earlier this year agreed to plead guilty to six felonies
and pay $650 million to resolve fraud allegations stemming from the
government's lengthy Wall Street insider trading investigation.
   It also agreed to dozens of administrative changes and
unprecedented federal supervision in the April settlement of civil
charges by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Most states can revoke a firm's right to do business if it is
convicted of or admits to committing a felony. Drexel also must
settle with Puerto Rico and the District of Columbia.
   ``Our objective is to retain our regulatory license in the 52
jurisdictions in which we do business,'' Drexel spokesman Steven
Anreder said. ``We're there already and we've already qualified and
we think it's proper as a good corporate citizen to do that.''
   The 10 states with which Drexel has reached agreements are
Arkansas, Hawaii, Idaho, Kansas, Maryland, Mississippi, Oklahoma,
South Carolina, Vermont and Wyoming.
   Oklahoma state securities administrator Susan Bryant, who headed
the Drexel settlement panel, said 20 other states have indicated
they expect to reach a pact under the basic agreement with some
additional provisions.
   Two or three holdout states want to revoke Drexel's license,
while settlements with the remaining jurisdictions still are
unresolved, Bryant said. She wouldn't name the holdouts.
   ``I think this approach has enabled smaller states to enter into
agreements with Drexel where they wouldn't have been able to if they
had been on their own,'' she said.
   Under the settlements, Drexel is contributing money to establish
a national foundation to promote investor education and securities
law compliance. That's an acceptable alternative to some state
securities regulators that lack fining authority or don't want to
lose the money to a general budget fund.
   ``I didn't want to structure this as a fine,'' said Ellyn Brown,
state securities commissioner in Maryland, which Drexel has agreed
to pay $200,000. ``It concerns me a little bit that the next people
in the door could say, `You sold Drexel their license _ how much for
us?' That appears to me as potentially problematic.''
   In Arkansas, Drexel is paying $100,000 even though the state has
no evidence Drexel did anything wrong there. In Oklahoma, Drexel
will pay $25,000 to reimburse fees for the securities division's
work but no fine. In Kansas, the $125,000 fine is designated for the
state's general fund.
   South Carolina is using its $150,000 to endow a chair in business
and ethics at the University of South Carolina's law school.
   Settling with the states relieves Drexel of possible litigation
by individual states and frees state regulators from having to
investigate the firm's trading activities from 1984 to 1986, when
the alleged SEC fraud occurred.
   The general pact requires Drexel's outside consultant to examine
possible state securities law violations and sets conditions on
Drexel's re-entry into the retail brokerage business, which Drexel
quit in April.
   It also requires Drexel to spread the word through newspaper
advertisements to investors who may be entitled to restitution under
the SEC settlement. Drexel has agreed to set aside $350 million for
investors and pay $300 million in fines to the government.
   Drexel faces class action lawsuits nationwide, some of which have
been consolidated in federal court in New York, by investors who
claim they were defrauded. Those who may be entitled to restitution
include people who bought stocks in 20 allegedly fraudulent
transactions cited by the SEC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890814-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-14 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher against major foreign
currencies in brisk trading Monday, extending last week's strong
rally.
   Gold prices also rose. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold bullion for current delivery closed at $367.10 a troy ounce, up
$1.90 from Friday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late
bid for gold at $364.70 an ounce, up $1.20.
   Dealers said demand for the dollar held steady from Friday, when
the currency jumped to its highest levels since early summer on
speculation that U.S. interest rates won't decline any time soon.
   Interest rates soared in the credit markets Monday, with some
rates reaching a nearly two-month high.
   ``At the moment no one is focusing on lower interest rates,''
said Robert Ryan, a senior trader at Irving Trust Co.
   The dollar had fallen earlier in the month as traders expressed
concern the Federal Reserve might loosen its credit policies by
working to lower interest rates to prevent the economy from falling
into a recession.
   But economic data released on Friday suggested that inflation may
be abating while the economy continues to expand. The government
reported a moderate drop in July wholesale prices and a
higher-than-expected jump in retail sales during the same period.
   ``When the dollar came down, it came down a long way so we're
seeing a reversal going on here. Money is flowing back into the
United States,'' Irving Trust's Ryan explained.
   Lower interest rates are seen as bearish for the dollar because
it makes dollar-denominated securities, such as bonds, less
attractive to foreign investors. As foreign interest declines so
does the need to convert foreign currencies into dollars.
   Overseas, the dollar turned mixed Monday, with many traders
taking to the sidelines before Tuesday's Assumption Day religious
holiday, which will close many European markets.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.83 yen to a closing 141.93 yen. It was quoted at
141.70 yen in London, and at 141.925 yen in New York, up from 141.90
Friday.
   The dollar gained slightly against the British pound. It cost
$1.5840 for sterling in London, compared with $1.5850 late Friday.
One pound fetched $1.5770 in New York, down from $1.5820 Friday.
   Other dollar rates at Monday's close compared with late Friday,
included: 1.9485 West German marks, up from 1.9405; 1.6805 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6755; 6.5780 French francs, up from 6.5555;
1.17955 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17455; and 1,399.00 Italian
lire, from 1,395.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Friday: 1.9395 West
German marks, up from 1.9390; 1.6760 Swiss francs, up from 1.6705;
6.5535 French francs, up from 6.5455; 2.1832 Dutch guilders, up from
2.1685; 1.1775 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1754; and 1,393.75
Italian lire, up from 1,388.00.
   Gold was steady in Europe. Gold closed in London at a bid price
of $364 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's 362.00. In Zurich,
the bid price was $363.50, up from $361.00 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 7 cents to close at a bid
$364.30 an ounce.
   Silver prices also increased. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.195 a troy ounce from $5.192 Friday.
Silver gained in London to $5.21 a troy ounce from $5.10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
