<HEAD>Bank Acquires San Francisco Investment Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Trust Corp. announced Monday it has
acquired the San Francisco investment management firm of Berry,
Hartell &amp; Evers.
   The West Coast firm, which was formed by the 1984 mergers of two
of the oldest investment companies in California, manages stock and
bond portfolios totaling about $285 million in assets for
individuals and pension and endowment funds.
   Details of the acquisition were not released. The firm will
become a wholly-owned subsidiary of Northern Trust after receiving
federal and state regulatory approvals.
   Northern Trust Corp. is the bank holding company for Northern
Trust Co., and is Chicago's fourth largest bank.
   On June 30, the company reported assets totaling $10.5 billion
and had trusts assets under administration that totaled nearly $200
billion.
   In 1988, the company opened Northern Trust of California and now
has offices in Los Angeles, Santa Barbara, San Francisco, Newport
Beach and San Diego.
