<FILEID>AP-NR-08-14-89 1758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-14 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Miners' Strike Push Up Copper Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper prices surged Monday on New York's Commodities Exchange in
the wake of a miners' strike in Peru and expectations that copper
will be in short supply in coming months.
   In other markets, grain and soybean prices dropped, energy
futures were mostly lower, precious metals were up modestly, and
meat and pork futures were off.
   Copper settled 2.75 cents to 3 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in August at $1.2035 a pound.
   The strike in Peru had been planned for several weeks, but it was
expected that efforts by the government would prevent the walkout.
Talks broke down over the weekend, resulting in the walkout.
   ``At least two-thirds if not more of the miners are out,'' said
John Steel, an analyst with Refco Co. in New York, adding that the
walkout could have an adverse effect on supplies.
   The strike comes as copper production is already suffering due to
civilian strife in Papua, New Guinea. Also, a strike at Canada's
Highland Valley Copper Mine in British Columbia continues.
   Copper production in Chile could also be disrupted because
drought has cut power supplies, Steel said.
   Grain and soybean futures closed lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade as traders reacted to forecasts of rain in crop-producing
areas.
   Soybean prices were down sharply, after rising last week on an
Agriculture Department report projecting lower-than-expected soybean
production.
   ``All of the speculators who bought Friday were seen selling
aggressively on Monday,'' said William Biedermann, an analyst with
Allendale Inc. in Chicago. ``Rain in the forecast was the main
reason.''
   Forecasts on Friday called for dry conditions. But Monday's
forecasts called for rain in eastern crop areas early this week, and
rain in western areas later in the week.
   ``Rain in August assures soybean producers a good crop,''
Biedermann said.
   Another factor on the soybean market is the South American
soybean crop, he said.
   Exports from South America are meeting international demand
before the U.S. harvest. Without sales from Brazil and Argentina,
the market would be tight, Biedermann said.
   Wheat futures rallied towards the close of trading, as traders
factored in Taiwan's bid for 300,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat.
   Wheat settled 1 cent lower to a { cent higher with September at
$3.97 a bushel; corn was 3\ cents to 6\ cents lower with September
at $2.27} a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 6 cents lower with
September at $1.36{ a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 20{ cents
lower with August at $6.02{ a bushel.
   Trading in precious metals was described as dull by Steel despite
the gains recorded by gold because of weakness in the dollar.
   Gold was $1.70 to $2.20 higher with August at $367.10 a troy
ounce; silver was .2 cent to .8 cent higher with August at $5.195 a
troy ounce.
   Livestock futures closed lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, as traders looked ahead to this week's Department of
Agriculture report on the number of cattle in feeding lots.
   It is expected the report will show heavier placements in feed
lots and lighter marketings than a year ago, said Tom Morgan, an
analyst with Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Pork prices were mixed, with support coming from expectations of
strong holiday demand for pork products.
   Live cattle settled .65 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August
at 74.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .25 cent
lower with August at 84.97 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower
to .22 cent higher with August at 47.07 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to .58 cent higher with August at 25.15 cents
a pound.
   Energy futures were mixed in quiet trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``I think the market is satisfied with current prices,'' said
Robert Baker, an analyst with Prudential Bache Securities Inc. in
New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 12 cents lower to 10 cents
higher with September at $18.58 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
to .16 cent lower with September at 50.04 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .08 cent to .63 cent lower with September at 52.09
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
