<HEAD>Ford Explorer Truck to be Shown to Dealers Beginning This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new truck from Ford Motor Co. called the
Explorer will be shown to dealers beginning this week in advance of
its formal unveiling next spring, Ford Division General Manager
Thomas Wagner said Monday.
   The new sport-utility vehicle, which will serve as a replacement
for the Bronco II, will be offered in two- and four-door models and
will be made at the company's Louisville truck plant.
   Further details of the vehicle were unavailable, said company
spokeswoman Anne Booker. It will be described to Ford dealers
beginning Wednesday during closed meetings in Chicago.
   She declined to say if the Explorer would be made for both Ford
and Mazda dealerships, but all indications pointed to that being the
case.
   In April, Ford officials in Louisville said the company would
make trucks at that plant for Mazda dealers. Ford owns 25 percent of
Mazda Motor Corp. of Japan, the parent company for a variety of
companies in the United States.
   Production of the Bronco II will stop in mid-January and
production of the Explorer will begin the following month.
   Currently, Ford and Mazda have a manufacturing agreement
involving Mazda's plant in Flat Rock. Ford Probes and Mazda MX-6
cars are built side-by-side at that plant south of Detroit.
