<FIRST>r f AM-Argentina-Debt     08-14 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Debt,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Wants to Reschedule IMF Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will try to
reschedule its debt to the International Monetary Fund in talks
later this month, Economy Minister Nestor Rapanelli said Monday.
   Argentina virtually stopped interest payments in April 1988 on
the approximately $63 billion it owes to commercial banks and
governmental institutions like the IMF. Principal payments were
deferred in 1987.
   Total overdue payments amount to about $4.4 billion, Foreign
Minister Domingo Cavallo said last week.
   The Central Bank discloses few details about Argentina's debt,
and the total owed to the IMF is not clear. The newspaper La Nacion,
citing sources in the Economy Ministry, reported last month the
country is $620 million behind in payments owed to the IMF.
   Rapanelli met Monday with U.S. Assistant Treasury Secretary David
Mulford and discussed the program of budget austerity and
privatizations proposed by President Carlos Menem to stabilize the
economy and promote growth, the government news agency Telam
reported.
   ``There was a clear manifestation ... of the favorable attitude
of the U.S. State Department and the president that they are
supporting this stage of economic recovery,'' Rapanelli said.
   Mulford later was set to meet wtih Menem.
   Inflation in July was almost 200 percent, and unemployment has
soared in the recession that was touched off by a run on the Central
Bank's foreign exchange reserves, and a massive devaluation of the
austral.
   Menem, who was elected in May and inaugurated in July, would like
to reschedule Argentina's commercial and private debt, and arrange
new loans, including $1.5 billion from the IMF and a $350 million
bridge loan from the U.S. Treasury.
</TEXT>
