<FIRST>r f AM-PhonePatent     08-14 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Patent,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds One Nokia Phone Patent; Knocks Down Two Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. administrative law judge has
recommended upholding a Nokia Corp. patent design of cellular mobile
telephones, but ruled against the company in two other patent
disputes brought by Motorola Inc., officials said Monday.
   Judge John J. Mathias in Washington recommended to the
International Trade Commission against Nokia on its patent for the
phone's keypad and temperature control device, said officials for
both companies.
   The Finnish telecommunications company's North American unit,
Nokia Inc., is based in Basking Ridge, N.J. The company said it
expects the trade commission to throw out the administrative law
judge's recommendation on the two component patents.
   Motorola, based in Schaumburg, Ill., filed patent infringement
complaints with the ITC and in federal court in Chicago in April to
try to block the import of certain cellular telephones.
   Nokia and Tandy Corp. jointly make cellular telephones in South
Korea to be are sold under separate brand names. Tandy markets the
phones under its Radio Shack brand name and Nokia under the name
Nokia-Mobira.
   Motorola is seeking to temporarily bar Nokia and Tandy from
importing the cellular phones and, in the federal court proceeding,
is asking for unspecified monetary damages.
   ``The ruling was clearly very favorable to Motorola,'' said
Motorola spokesman Tim Kellogg.
   The ITC is to make an initial finding by Aug. 29, when the
commission would decide how large a bond the two companies must post
so they can continue selling the imported phones until a final
decision.
   The case is expected to be resolved next April.
</TEXT>
