<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude, Heating Oil Futures Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil and heating oil futures finished mostly
lower Monday in listless trading, as the market continued in its
summer doldrums with no significant events on the horizon to
influence price movements. Gasoline futures were mixed.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September-delivery
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude, closed 10 cents higher at $18.58 per 42-gallon barrel. Most
contract months for later delivery declined, however.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded regular
gasoline for September delivery jumped 0.63 cent to 52.09 cents a
gallon. Many contracts for later delivery fell.
   Heating oil futures declined after leading the market higher last
week. The September contract slipped 0.16 cent to finish at 50.04
cents a gallon. Other contracts had smaller declines.
   Analysts said the market turned in a dull performance, with no
fresh news to influence prices. They said traders are looking
forward to Labor Day for a pickup in activity and beyond that to the
next scheduled meeting, on Sept. 23, of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``Fundamentally, there's no change in the market,'' said Linda
Simard, an oil futures analyst at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
``Everyone's wondering when this is going to end.''
