<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     08-14 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Higher, Share Prices Rise Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar traded higher against the Japanese
yen Tuesday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
rose marginally as many participants took summer holidays.
   The dollar opened at 142.40 yen, up 0.47 yen from Monday's close
of 141.93 yen, the ending rate in New York also.
   Its higher start followed a similar uptrend on overseas markets,
traders said.
   Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said early
dealing was initiated by Japanese commercial banks, which were
mainly buying the dollar.
   ``There was little dollar-selling incentive now in the market, so
the dollar was getting stronger against other currencies, too,'' she
said.
   The dollar's upswing began when the U.S. jobless rate was
released two weeks ago and the nation's unemployment rate fell by
0.1 percent in July.
   Market players were further reassured about the steady growth in
the U.S. economy by a 0.4 percent decline in the producer price
index and a 0.9 percent rise in the retail price index for July,
both released Friday in Washington.
   ``The dollar was moving little after the opening, and partcipants
are not energetic enough to push the currency over the 143-yen
mark,'' Ms. Takeuchi said, adding that trading was thin because many
investors are on summer vacations this week.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues grew by 3.03
points, or 0.01 percent, to reach 34,674.65 within the first 15
minutes of morning trading.
   Dealers said trading was inactive also due to summer holidays.
</TEXT>
